<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese government, Rebel Group to Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Sudanese
government left here today for the Kenyan capital of Nairobi to
hold peace negotiations with a main rebel group.
</P>
<P>
The government delegation, headed by Foreign Minister Ali Osman
Mohamed Taha, is scheduled to start negotiation Tuesday with Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) led by John Garang under the
auspices of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and
Development of eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has reportedly voiced doubts about the
outcome of the forthcoming negotiations due to the fact that the
rebel delegation is not headed by Garang himself, but his deputy,
who the government believes not to have the final say.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA and several other rebel factions have been fighting
the Islamic government since 1983 for greater autonomy for the
Christian and animist south.
</P>
<P>
The government and four factions signed last April a peace
agreement, under which the southerners would be given the right to
self-determination at the end of a transitional period. But the
SPLA rejected to sign the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
