<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong PC Market Growth Seen in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- World personal computer market
showed a six percent growth in the third quarter of 1997,
according to the International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The performance was 16 percent higher than the same period
1996, the Massachussets-based IDC said today in its preliminary
data release.
</P>
<P>
Analysts at the IDC, a global information technology market
research and consulting company, attribute the boom to increasing
demand driven by lower price points and new technologies.
</P>
<P>
Supported by a healthy economy, the United States market
sustained a 20 percent surge for the third straight quarter, IDC
said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's market declined 12 percent in the quarter, the first
plunge in 18 months, it added.
</P>
<P>
Other regions displayed mixed results with Asia Pacific
fetching 20 percent growth and Western Europe a
better-than-expected growth of 14 percent, driven by strong
demand in the business and consumer markets of France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. company Compaq was the best performer with a 52 percent
increase in its worldwide unit shipments due to its new price
strategy. Its worldwide market share widened to 14 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
