<HEADLINE> Cambodian Leader Hun Sen to Run for Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Hun Sen, Cambodia's second
prime minister and vice-president of the Cambodian People's Party
(CPP), said today that he will be the only candidate from the CPP
to run for the position of prime minister in next year's polls.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen told reporters at the conclusion of the 23rd session of
the fifth congress of the CPP that his candidacy will not change
this year or the next year.
</P>
<P>
Terming the reports on the split in the CPP as sheer
fabrication, Hun Sen noted, "There will be no discussion on who is
to be the CPP candidate for the post of prime minister as long as
I am alive."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, CPP spokesman Khieu Kanharith told reporters that
the three-million member CPP will try to get 73 of the National
Assembly's 120 seats in next year's polls.
</P>
<P>
The CPP is optimistic about its victory in the polls, Kanharith
said. Even if the CPP lost, the winner could not rule the country
without the CPP's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"If the CPP wins, we will also establish a coalition government
with other parties," he added.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the Central Committee of the CPP said
the elections next May will be organized by Cambodia and
supervised by the international community. The CPP said it will
respect the results of the polls.
</P>
<P>
However, Kanharith said the CPP will seek to conduct the polls
on May 23 next year. He cannot, however, rule out the possibility
of postponing the polls until next September.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said that a special national congress of
the CPP will be held in February 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
