<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Self-employed Earnings Polarized in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The earnings of self-employed in
Canada has become more polarized, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the averaged self-employed person in this country made
30,800 dollars, which was about 91 percent earned by the average
employee.
</P>
<P>
At the low end of the scale, about 45 percent of the
self-employed made less than 20,000 dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
At the other end, 4.2 percent of the self-employed made more
than 100,000 dollars, according to today's Globe and Mail
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The highest earners among the self-employed were business
owners in the social sciences -- people like lawyers, economists,
sociologists and psychologists.
</P>
<P>
They earned an average of 85,000 dollars and were followed by
those in medical occupations, who earned 73,800 dollars, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The self-employed accounted for 75 percent of the new jobs
created in Canada between 1989 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
They now account for about 17 percent of all workers in this
country, up from 14 percent in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
