<HEADLINE> WTO: No "Global" Trading System Without Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero said here today that the
world can never have a truly "global" trading system without the
full integration of the least-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero was speaking at the opening session of an inter-agency
meeting on Integrated Initiatives for Least Developed Countries'
(LDCs) Trade Development.
</P>
<P>
"It is an enormously important meeting," Ruggiero told
participants from WTO members and representatives and ministers
from 39 LDCs, present at the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
He called on the participants to produce meaningful results,
results that will be of real and practical significance to the
LDCs.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was jointly sponsored by WTO, the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), the
International Trade Center (ITC), a joint subsidiary of UNCTAD and
WTO, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Participants will have a series of roundtable sessions during
the meeting. The secretariats of the six agencies taking part in
the meeting will offer assistance in their respective areas of
expertise to the 12 LDCs for which roundtable sessions have been
organized.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, WTO members will have a chance to announce
steps they are taking to enhance their market access for imports
for LDCs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
