<HEADLINE> 2,000 People Demonstrate in Berlin to Support Scientology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 people from various
countries joined a demonstration in Berlin today protesting over
the alleged discrimination against Scientology in Germany.
</P>
<P>
At a rally outside the Kaiser Wilhelm memorial church in
central Berlin, U.S. actor John Travolta said: "The primary
problem in Germany is the unfair persecution of Scientology and
other minority religions by the government without factual
justification."
</P>
<P>
Scientologists in Germany have been put under surveillance by
the country's domestic security service since early this year when
interior ministers from 16 federal states concluded the
organization posed a threat to democracy.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, neo-Nazis and left extremist parties are being
likewise treated.
</P>
<P>
Bonn had also considered using overseas intelligence service to
monitor Scientologists abroad, and only decided not to do this 10
days ago.
</P>
<P>
Recognized as a religious sect in the United States,
Scientology is but accepted as an enterprise with economic goals
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in a statement refuting an accusation by a U.S. senator
that Scientology was being persecuted in Germany, German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel described it as a "quasi-totalitarian"
organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
