<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Congo Plan to Set up National Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- France today welcomed the
announcement by the new president of Congo Republic, Denis
Sassou-Nguesso, to set up a government of national union, after
the latter was sworn in as president last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good thing," said French Foreign Ministry
spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt. "It is essential that Congo,
ravaged by war, engage itself fully on the way of national
reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
He said that in his swearing-in speech, Sassou-Nguesso had
"traced the great lines of transition which is opening itself and
which should lead to general elections" in Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that France hopes the United Nations can
"play a role" in the national reconciliation process of Congo
Republic, including sending observers to supervise the process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French ambassador to Congo, Raymond Cesaire, is
now in the Congolese economic capital Pointe-Noire to seek the
release of three Frenchmen arrested by the forces of
Sassou-Nguesso for smuggling arms to the troops of former
president, Pascal Lissouba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
