<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Libya Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela is set to revisit Libya Wednesday, the second of
its kind within five days, the president office announced in Cape
Town today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's return to Libya would be "a very brief visit
touching on matters arising out of his recent visit there," the
office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He will be making no announcement and is not intending to hold
a press conference in connection with the visit, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The president office declined to give more details about
Mandela's coming visit to Libya.
</P>
<P>
But government officials who asked not to be identified said
Mandela would give Libyan leader M. Gaddafi an official
decoration and tell him attitudes of Commonwealth leaders to
impose sanctions against the north African country.
</P>
<P>
Last week Mandela had a one-day visit to Libya where he held
talks with Gaddafi over possible resolutions for the Lockerbie
dispute. He is now in Edinburgh, Scotland for a Commonwealth
summit which is due to end today.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie dispute was erupted after an explosion of a
Pan-Am airliner over the Scottish town of Lockerbie. The air
tragedy claimed 270 lives.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain claimed that Libya intelligents
were involved in the incident, and demanded two Libyan suspects
be handed over for trial in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya's resistance to the Western allegation and extradition
demand has resulted in United Nations' sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
