<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Push for Investment Screening Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada is insisting on
continuing to screen foreign investment under a proposed
multilateral agreement to liberate global investment, a report
said today.
</P>
<P>
As talks resume this week in Paris, the Canadian government is
pushing for a long list of exemptions that would allow the
screening of foreign takeovers to ensure companies maintain
research and employment in this country.
</P>
<P>
According to a leaked copy of the list, Canada is also seeking
the right to adopt or maintain any social program that is in the
public interest and to maintain foreign ownership restrictions in
telecommunications and financial services.
</P>
<P>
The 29 members of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) are hoping to conclude a deal by next spring
that would ensure countries provide the same treatment to foreign
corporations as they do to their domestic companies.
</P>
<P>
Other OECD countries have also submitted reservation lists,
though the United States is pushing for a wide open deal,
according to today's Globe and Mail newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
