<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltic States Dislike Russia's Security Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia
have expressed their dislike for the security guarantees offered
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The security guarantees proposed by Russia to the Baltic
nations are "nearly protectorate," Chairman of the Lithuanian
Parliament Vytautas Landsbergis told Interfax news agency today in
Vilnius, Capital of Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin gave the visiting Lithuanian president a document
Friday in Moscow on security guarantees for the Baltic countries.
</P>
<P>
"A protectorate status cannot be imposed through a unilateral
decision," Landsbergis said. "To put the proposals into practice,
Lithuania would have to accept them by signing an appropriate
agreement and becoming Russia's guarded state," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Lithuanian constitution bans such
post-Soviet defense unions, saying that "if the West confirms that
the security guarantees will contribute to speeding up the Baltic
countries' entry into the European Union and NATO, Yeltsin's
proposals can be assessed positively."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Estonian foreign ministry said that Estonia is
guided by the principle of "indivisibility of European security,"
and cannot rely on guarantees offered by one country.
</P>
<P>
An Estonian diplomat said the Estonian foreign ministry has not
yet received the complete statement from Russia and that "upon
receiving it we shall thoroughly analyze the Russian proposals."
</P>
<P>
Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis said on October 25 that Latvia
has not demanded any security guarantees from Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Security guarantees are not the sort of things one side
chooses for the other," Ulmanis said.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia stated on many occasions that
only membership in NATO can fully guarantee their security. The
three countries are therefore actively seeking admission to NATO,
which is strongly opposed by Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
