<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Act for Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official today
urged member states of the Common Market for the Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) to take action for a co-ordinated
regional development in transport and communications.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day meeting on transport and communications held
here in the capital, Dawson Lupunga, Minister of Communications
and Transport, said development in this regard is key to the
promotion of economic development and the integration of the
COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency Zana quoted Lupunga as saying that without
transport and communications, trade and interaction in the region
would be adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his concern over the slow pace and in some cases
the "outright failure" by some COMESA members to implement
programs aimed at achieving the intended goal of the 23-member
regional body.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which was established in 1994 and groups 23 members
including Angola, Ethiopia, Kenya, Mozambique, Sudan and Zambia,
aims to achieve a full free trade area by 2000, a customs union
with zero tariff and free movement of people in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some members, said the Zambian minister, have not yet
established what are called multi-disciplinary working groups and
mechanisms for monitoring and facilitating the implementation of
agreed COMESA programs.
</P>
<P>
Lupunga also urged COMESA and its secretariat to keep in step
with the current development trends in information technology
strategies so as to enhance the exchange of vital information
between the secretariat and its member states.
</P>
<P>
He said COMESA members should ensure that the advanced cargo
information system, in which Uganda, Kenya, Tanzania and Zambia
have taken the lead, is implemented for all the railway networks
as well as all major ports of the member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
