<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Body on Lake Victoria Poised to Take off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Three years after it was
created, the Lake Victoria Fisheries Organization aimed at
protecting the eco-system of Lake Victoria is about to begin
operations, the East African newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ntiba (only identified with one name), executive secretary
of the agency, said Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania will contribute up
to 7,000 U.S. Dollars each year toward a common fund for the
organization based in Jinja, eastern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
However, 21,000 Dollars put together by the three governments
will constitute only 10 percent of the total budget of the body
for the next five years, said Ntiba.
</P>
<P>
The remaining funding is expected to come from
non-governmental organizations including the Global Environmental
Facility, he added.
</P>
<P>
The body will be focused on coordinating efforts by the three
governments to preserve the environment of the lake and to
improve the lakeside industry.
</P>
<P>
The fresh water lake, the second largest in the world, is the
main source of livelihood for more than 40 million people in the
eastern African region.
</P>
<P>
However, the eco-system of Lake Victoria has been under threat
since 1990 from the fast-spreading water hyacinth, which is
choking the lake and hindering fishing and lake travel.
</P>
<P>
Each of the three eastern African states has been grappling
with the water hyacinth but none has yet come up with concrete
plans to control the weed.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government recently rejected the use of chemicals
to curb the spread of the water hyacinth, arguing that it could
adversely affect the country's lucrative fish industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
