<HEADLINE> No Plan to Join EMU Before Next Election: Brown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) - The British Government does not
intend to join a single European Currency before the next
election, Chancellor Gordon Brown said.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor told parliament this afternoon: "Barring some
fundamental and unforeseen circumstances, making a decision during
this parliament to join is not realistic."
</P>
<P>
Brown's statement was aimed to return the government an even
keel after several weeks of buffeting by markets and media over
its handling of the EMU decision.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chancellor said the Treasury had concluded that in
principle membership of the single currency would be of benefit to
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Brown made it clear that if the economic benefits were "clear
and unambiguous", Britain should join EMU.
</P>
<P>
But, the Chancellor restated that any recommendation to join
would have to be approved in a referendum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
