<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalia Plagued by Heavy Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The heavy rains of the Deyr
season continue to inflict losses to both human lives and
livestock in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people have died when they were drowned in
torrential floods from Jubba river which burst the bank of the
regions of Middle Jubba, Bay Bakol and Gedo of Southwestern
Somalia as heavy rain kept pouring down in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the town of Tiyeglow in Bakol
region, 30 houses were destroyed as the water rose to a height of
1.5 meters above the ground level, thus forcing residents of the
town to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
In the village of Biyoley, also in Bakol region, the floods
have claimed the lives of five people, and destroyed 15 houses.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Mo'allim Iman, an elder of Bay region, told the
reporters that the villages of Gof-Guduud, Bonkay, Ufurow and
Labatan Jirow were also severely affected by the floods and
rains.
</P>
<P>
In Gof-Gudud village, said the Iman, five children died and
more than 10,000 quintals of beans and sorghum were washed away.
All business activities in the region were stopped with all the
roads linking Qansah Dhere, Korombod and Habal Barbaar cut off by
the waters, he added.
</P>
<P>
Rahanwein elders in the region said, hundreds of families are
now fleeing the waters to the nearby main towns. Many of them are
now stranded in between the villages without enough food while a
large number have moved to the towns of Huddor, Luq and Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
According to the elders, so far there are no aid agencies
operating to cope with the floods and rains of the season as the
elders keep appealing for the international community for dry
food, medicine, tents and clothes.
</P>
<P>
The town of Luq in the Gedo region has been isolated by waters
from other neighboring villages and towns after all roads leading
to and fro it were filled with the waters.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle, spokesman for Rahanwein Resistance
Army (RRA) in Mogadishu has called on the international NGOs to
help the Rahanwein communities whose people cannot run to the
towns of Baidoa or Huddor for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle said, as many as 360 goats and 45 houses were
destroyed by the waters in the areas which were under their
control since the beginning of this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
