<HEADLINE> Kenya, Uganda to Sign Pipeline Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Uganda are expected
to sign a contract Wednesday for extending an oil pipeline from
western Kenya's Eldoret to Kampala, the capital of Uganda, a
local report said today.
</P>
<P>
The contract, funded by the European Investment Bank, is to be
signed in Kampala by Kenyan Minister of Finance Musalia Mudavadi
and his Ugandan counterpart Jehoash Mayanja-Nkangi, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
The Eldoret-Kampala oil pipeline would reduce transport costs
not only to Uganda, but also to Rwanda, Burundi and the eastern
part of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Uganda currently pays 20 U.S. Dollars for per ton of oil from
Eldoret instead of Mombasa, the Indian Ocean port of Kenya. It
always complains that it spends too much money on road transport.
</P>
<P>
Kenya regulations prohibit the ferrying of fuel from Nairobi
or Mombasa by road, but rail haulage is still permitted.
</P>
<P>
Although the Eldoret pipeline allows transporters a two-day
return journey by road, compared to more than four days if the
oil is fetched from Mombasa, the latter alternative is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
But Kenya argues that its demand that all oil destined for
Uganda should be collected from Eldoret is a way of curbing the
destruction of its roads by heavy haulage trucks.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Uganda is also actively engaged in the
proposed Dar-es-Salaam-Mwanza oil pipeline project as an
alternative oil outlet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
