<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Refuses to Return More Land to PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said here this evening that no more land will
be handed over to the Palestinians unless the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) fulfill its commitment to fight terror.
</P>
<P>
In his policy address to the Knesset (parliament), Netanyahu
said that Israel wants to advance the peace process, but there
will be no unilateral fulfillment of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the PNA for not doing enough in fighting terrorism,
saying it is still violating its commitment and pledge to combat
terror.
</P>
<P>
He declared that Israel will continue Jewish settlement
activities in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and Jerusalem will
remain as the unified capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Israel's relations with Syria, he said that any
agreement with Syria must take into account that Syria should not
maintain its capability of launching surprise attacks against
Israel and that Israel must continue to retain water sources in
the north bordering Syria.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention if Israel will continue to occupy the Golan
Heights, but said the Heights is very important to Israel and vital
to Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
As for the South Lebanon issue, he said that Israel will not
withdraw its troops unilaterally. Any agreement related to South
Lebanon must be linked to the dismantle of the Hezbollah (Party of
God) forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Iran's missile issue, he said that Israel will,
both in political and intelligential ways, try its best to reduce
the threat of Iran's buildup of long-range missiles with the help
of Russia, because that poses a direct threat to Israeli security
and existence.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset, which opened its winter session today after a
three-months recess, faced a stormy sitting from the very
beginning.
</P>
<P>
As Netanyahu touched upon the proposed budget for 1998 with
deep cuts on education, health and military expenditure,
opposition parliament members (MPs) started attacking him for
leading the country into a mess.
</P>
<P>
The opposition MPs from Labor and Meretz parties hoped to turn
the vote of Netanyahu's policy address into a no-confidence
motion even if it means delaying the vote for a week.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Knesset has 120 members, with Netanyahu's coalition
government taking 66 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
