<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Cases Rise as Attention Shifted to AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's tuberculosis
(TB) cases have increased sharply as more attention have been
shifted to combat HIV/AIDS infection, according to a survey by
Southern Africa Control Initiative (SATCI).
</P>
<P>
The survey, made available today, says that at least one third
of Tanzania's TB cases are indirectly attributable to HIV/AIDS
infection. Tanzania is one of the countries where the onslaught
on HIV/AIDS has caused more TB deaths.
</P>
<P>
The report said Tanzania's TB control program used to serve as
a model in the world for controlling TB effectively with the
highest TB cure rates from 1977 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
Matters changed when the country was slammed by the deadly
HIV/AIDS in 1984. "As a result of HIV's onslaught, the TB control
program was swamped with new TB cases," it said.
</P>
<P>
Whereas the global average on TB incidence was 60 cases per
100,000 people for last year, in Tanzania it is 134 per 100,000.
There were 39,847 TB cases in Tanzania then with 24,980 newly
infected.
</P>
<P>
According to SATCI, eleven Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC) countries are struggling under "the greatest TB
burden" with 168 TB cases per 10,000 people, nearly three times
the world average level.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, SADC countries had an estimated 227,156 people
reported to have TB with 152,198 of them found out to be newly
infected. Tanzania is the second in TB cases after South Africa
which had 84,750.
</P>
<P>
TB is an infectious disease whose bacteria can remain
undetected in the body for many years. It attacks many parts of
the body especially the lungs.
</P>
<P>
Within the SADC region, the spread of the disease has been
fuelled by large immigration worker flows, refugees and periodic
surges of displaced people.
</P>
<P>
"The mass movements generally result in interruptions of TB
treatment and disruptive changes in treatment schedules and
medications," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise of HIV/AIDS has caused dramatic rise in TB
deaths and its spread across the region especially in the past
decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
