<HEADLINE> US, UK Welcome Ideas of Ending Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Britain would welcome any intervention to break the deadlock over
the venue for the trial of two Libyans suspected of the 1988
Lockerbie Bombing, South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
said today.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki told reporters in Pretoria that President Nelson Mandela
was interested in facilitating a conclusion of the Lockerbie
dispute.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied both the government of the U.S. and the UK
will appreciate any intervention which breaks the logjam," He
said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the suspects might be tried in South Africa, Mbeki
said this was still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the families of the Scottish victims on
Sunday said South Africa would be acceptable as a neutral venue
for the trial, an offer first made by Mandela in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A crisis was erupted between Libya and Western countries after
the United States and Britain claimed Libyan intelligents were
involved in the bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland that killed 270 people nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London have been demanding two Libyan suspects
be handed over for trial in Scotland. But Libya, the Organization
of African Unity and the Arab League insist that the suspects
should be tried in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who had a brief visit to Libya last week, came out in
support of Libyan leader Gaddafi's refusal to extradite the two
suspects.
</P>
<P>
"I have never thought it is correct for any country to be
complainant, prosecutor and judge," Mandela told reporters at the
meeting of Commonwealth leaders in Edinburgh, Britain on last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a United Nations air and arms embargo
against Libya to be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
