<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Loses 200,000 Hectares of Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia said today it is
losing its natural forest at an estimated rate of 200,000
hectares per annum.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a training course here, Tamena Tirunneh,
environmental planning senior expert with the Ministry of
Economic Development and Cooperation, said the depletion has an
adverse effect on natural resources and it is continuing unabated
to meet demands for fire wood, farmland and construction
materials.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to replenish the dwindling natural resources is very
minimal despite the fact that the agricultural sector, the
backbone of the national economy, is totally dependent on the
resources, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The training, jointly organized by the ministry and the
Environmental Protection Authority, was aimed at drawing
attention to issues related to environmental economics during
project planning and review.
</P>
<P>
The forest coverage in Ethiopia is only three percent. The
decline of forest resources in the country has warned people to
protect their environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
