<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Receives 1.5 Billion Dollars Offset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has so far
received 1.5 billion U.S. dollars of investment commitment from
its arms suppliers under its Offset Program launched in 1992,
according to officials in charge of the Offset Program today.
</P>
<P>
They said the program is making steady progress with several
projects already up and running.
</P>
<P>
The offset program requires any foreign arms supplier winning
a contract worth more than 1 million Kuwaiti dinars (3.3 million
U.S. dollars) from the oil-rich emirate to reinvest 30 percent
of the contract's value in Kuwait or Kuwait's ventures abroad.
</P>
<P>
The program is mainly aimed at getting back some of the funds
which have poured out in defense contracts signed with mainly
its western allies since it started a massive rearmament plan
following the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 companies, almost exclusively defense companies,
have signed offset agreements with Kuwait, although a Japanese
civil company has also signed an offset deal.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Finance Minister Nasser Al-Rudhan told the Parliament
earlier that Kuwait currently had seven major offset projects
which are either being implemented or are under formation.
</P>
<P>
One of the largest projects approved under the offset program
is a plan to set up an aluminum plant with an annual capacity of
230,000 tons of aluminum. Raytheon Cooperation of the United
States is involved in the project. France and Britain also have
offset projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, most offset projects have been slow to get off the
ground and actual investment so far in the established offset
projects is about 50 million dollars, accounting for a small
fraction of the pledges, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, foreign companies rarely have to spend the full 30
percent of their contract's value.
</P>
<P>
After signing an offset agreement, a company must first
identify a suitable investment venture, have it approved and
then set up the new operation, which usually take three to five
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Favors Preemptive Strike on Missile Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said today he would favor launching preemptive
strikes to thwart missile and non-conventional weapon threats to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the statement in a key-note speech at an
international conference held in Tel Aviv to discuss missile and
non-conventional weapon proliferation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Experts from Israel, the United State, Europe and Jordan
presented papers to the meeting on weapon threats and the possible
establishment of certain regimes to prevent such threats.
</P>
<P>
The meeting put its emphasis on threats from Iran, Iraq, Syria
and Libya, which were alleged to have been striving to acquire
weapons of mass destruction. Mordechai said Israel must relate to
those threats and potential dangers "very seriously."
</P>
<P>
The minister outlined major factors in Israel's defense against
threats of long-range ballistic missiles and non-conventional
weapons:
</P>
<P>
- Israel will make every effort to prevent war; but in face of
threats from missiles with non-conventional warheads, it boasts
deterrent capabilities and will employ all necessary options at
disposal to prevent such threats.
</P>
<P>
- Israel has enough far-reaching capabilities to deal with
missile threats, including a missile-detecting system and the
"Arrow" missile-shooting system.
</P>
<P>
- Israel has the ability to strike all missile targets
threatening its security, including missile launchers and
storerooms.
</P>
<P>
- Israel owns a passive civil defense system to protect its
civilian population from missile threats, at least reducing the
possible casualties in attacks.
</P>
<P>
Finally, Mordechai warned that if any of its enemies will
strike Israel with missiles and non-conventional weapons, it will
have to pay a heavy price since Israel will strike back hardly.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's remarks came as Israel was making efforts to
persuade Russia to halt its alleged transfer of missile technology
to Iran, which is deemed No. 1 military threat to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai met with visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov this morning in Jerusalem to discuss Russian assistance
to Iran's weapons development programs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Foreign
Minister David Levy and other senior officials had already held
talks with Primakov in a bid to discourage Russia from continuing
its military cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Primakov strongly denied Russia's involvement in Iran's missile
and nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai expressed his regrets over Russia's refusal to accept
the Israeli demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
