<HEADLINE> Primakov Calls for Respecting Signed Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ramallah, (Palestine) October 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov today called on both Israel and the
Palestinians to respect the obligations to their signed agreements
in a bid to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the call here at a joint press conference with
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat after
a three-hour meeting to discuss the situation of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Primakov stressed that all parties, especially the Israeli
government, should respect the duties to carry out the Oslo
accords and other agreements.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Palestinians to fulfill its commitments to
the agreements by curbing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"It's very important that all parties will stick to their
obligations in the branch of security, because all terror acts
harm the Palestinian people and their cause," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Russia's continued support to the PNA and the
Palestinian cause for an independent state, which he said Russia
would recognize as soon as it is established.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Primakov called for the resumption of the peace
talks between Syria, Lebanon and Israel, saying it is very
important to achieve a stable and comprehensive peace in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed deep gratitude to Russia for its support to
the Palestinian cause and its efforts to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He called on Russian President Boris Yeltsin to mediate and
help save the peace process as a co-sponsor along with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, arriving here Sunday after visiting Lebanon, Syria
and Israel, was originally scheduled to visit Jordan later today
after meeting with Arafat. But he has decided to return to
Damascus for another round of talks with Syiran President Hafez
al-Assad as he reportedly has come up with "new ideas" on resuming
peace talks after the meetings with Syrian and Israeli leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
