<HEADLINE> Mandela Awarded Honorable Citizenship of Edinburgh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBUGH, October 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela has been awarded the honorable citizenship of Edinburgh as
a symbol of respect for his life-long battle for the freedom of
his country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after presenting the traditional "Freedom Scroll" to
Mandela, Lord Provost Eric Milligan said earlier this year
Edinburgh's councillors unanimously voted to offer the award to
recognize Mandella's "personal lifelong fight for the freedom of
South Africa".
</P>
<P>
"The Freedom of the City is the highest honor that we can
bestow on any individual and we are proud of honoring someone
whose personal strength, compassion and dignity has made him
admired around the world," Milligan said.
</P>
<P>
"At a political level, President Mandela has similarly proved
an inspiration for the example he has shown in bringing people
together and developing a shared vision for the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who is in Edinburgh attending Commonwealth summit,
said that he would regard it as a tribute to the whole South
Africa nation for the courage in the struggle for freedom.
</P>
<P>
"We are proud to be honored by men and women whose commitment
to freedom as an universal right has been demonstrated by many
years of support for the liberation of South and Southern Africa,"
Mandela said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
