<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The four-day 1997
Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting (CHOGM) ended at the
Edinburgh International Conference Center this afternoon with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair calling it an "immensely
successful" summit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the final press conference, Blair expressed
satisfaction over the achievements made over the the special theme
of the summit: "Trade, Investment and Development -- the Road to
Common Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Blair, who is also Chairman of the meeting, said that the
successful first ever Commonwealth Business Forum held in London
last week "reflects the significant change for the Commonwealth on
economic issues."
</P>
<P>
"Putting behind some of our controversies of the past, we are
now able to focus on issues of trade, investment, jobs and shared
prosperity for the future," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe very much together with other heads of government
we've prepared the Commonwealth to face the challenges of the next
century," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the final Edinburgh Communique, the Commonwealth leaders
hailed the Edinburgh Economic Declaration, issued on Saturday, as
a "fitting complement to the Harare Commonwealth Declaration in
1991."
</P>
<P>
The Harare Declaration, which put forward fundamental political
principles for the Commonwealth, is commonly regarded the
political pillar of the institution.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Nigeria, whose membership was suspended in 1995
because of alleged human rights violations, the Commonwealth
leaders expressed their deep concern and decided to maintain the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
The communique also points out that if the Nigerian government
failed to improve its human rights records by October 1 1998, the
Commonwealth would impose tough measures including mandatory oil
embargo, a ban on air-links with Nigeria and even expulsion from
the 54-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth leaders decided that the Commonwealth
Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) should continue to its standing
ministerial mechanism "to address serious and persistent violations
of the principles of Harare Declaration."
</P>
<P>
Over the next two years after the Edinburgh summit, the new
ministerial group would consist of the following eight countries:
Barbardos, Boswana, Britain, Canada, Ghana, Malaysia, New Zealand
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
On the criteria of admitting new Commonwealth members, the
Communique said that in order to become a new Commonwealth member,
an applicant country should have a "constitutional association"
with an existing Commonwealth member and should also promise to
comply with Commonwealth principles set out in the Harare
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Commonwealth leaders expressed their views on
the Cyprus problem, fighting international terrorism and other
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Under agreement reached among Commonwealth members, South
Africa will host the next Commonwealth summit meeting in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former French President Criticizes Tendency to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Former French President Valery
Giscard d'Estaing today criticized the tendency in France and
abroad to defame France through the on-going trial of former Vichy
official Maurice Papon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with daily Le Monde, d'Estaing said that the
role played by Vichy France during World War II is uncomparable
with that of Germany, which he said "was the player of history"
while France was subjected to its military occupation.
</P>
<P>
"Many rejoiced, notably in the Anglo-Saxon media, at an
affirmation of a recognition of guiltiness of France," said
d'Estaing.
</P>
<P>
Papon, a former official who served under the Vichy
collaboration regime led by Marshal Philippe Petain, is being
tried for crimes against humanity because of his role in the
deportation of 1,690 Jews from southwest to Nazi death camps from
1942 to 1944, when he was in charge of the "Jewish Question" in
the Gironde Prefecture of southwest France.
</P>
<P>
D'Estaing said that there exists "an expectation, a desire to
hear proclaim the guiltiness of France" by the court in Bordeaux
where Papon is standing trial.
</P>
<P>
Papon also served as the budget minister of a conservative
cabinet under d'Estaing in 1978.
</P>
<P>
D'Estaing said that during World War II, France was "less
defeated than it does not want to believe... and less collaborated
(with Germany) than one tries today to present it to."
</P>
<P>
"How many French houses are open to the Germans? Very few.
Which cities applauded when German garrison troops paraded through
them? None," said the former president.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the primary information on the role of
Papon during the occupation was released in 1981 and between the
two rounds of presidential election, when Francois Mitterrand was
posing as a presidential candidate for the Socialist Party against
the rightwing candidate, who was d'Estaing himself.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand, who won the presidency, refused to recognize the
responsibility of France for the deportation of 76,000 Jews from
France to Germany.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac recognized in 1995 that the "French
state" did the "irreparable" by deporting the Jews to Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eco-tourism to Become Fastest-Growing Segment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Tourism has become the most
important civil industry in the world and will continue to swell
up with nature-based eco-tourism the fastest segment, experts said
at an international eco-tourism conference which opened today.
</P>
<P>
International tourists arrivals will top one billion by 2010
with a much larger proportion of tourists drawn by eco-tourism,
the experts predicted.
</P>
<P>
Eco-tourism, defined by the Eco-tourism Society as "responsible
travel to natural areas that conserves the environment and
sustains the well-being of local people," was first popularized
in Latin America and then rooted in Africa in 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The eco-tourism experience can be dated back to nature tourism
which has flourished in the national parks of the Untied States
for over 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays eco-tourism, which focuses on the industry's quality
instead of quantity and try to have local communities benefited
from relevant natural resources, will represent the main trend of
future world travel market, the conference was told.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which is held here, with the theme as "eco-tourism
-- Charting the way forward," discussed today how to draft
eco-tourism principles and improve eco-tourism operation on the
continent in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
It was said to be the first-ever of this kind held in east
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Global and regional case studies on successful eco-tourism
models are to be discussed at the meeting which will end on
November 3.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the conference was an exhibition of
community-based tourism activities, showcasing the unique
heritage, handicrafts and tourism development efforts of Kenya's
40-plus diverse cultures.
</P>
<P>
More than 260 delegates from the U.S., Britain, South Africa,
Mexico, Brazil, Belize, Tanzania, Swaziland, Uganda, Australia,
Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique, Malawi, Zimbabwe and other
countries attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
World tourism hit a record high in 1996 with 593 million
international tourist arrivals, up 4.6 percent from the previous
year, according to the latest data from the World Tourism
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
