<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Remains Suspended From C'wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Nations
today decided in Edinburgh, Scotland, that it is not ready to
re-admit Nigeria into the 53-nation organization but it will not
impose new sanctions against Abuja at the moment.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria quoted a communique issued at the
end of the Commonwealth summit as saying that the heads of
government expressed satisfaction with Nigeria's political
transition program and decided to allow it to complete it.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, however, warned at a press
conference that measures would be taken against Nigeria "if there
is no progress in the transition program by October next year".
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in November
1995 after its government executed author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other minority activists on charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military government led by General Sani Abacha
has announced a transition program which promises to return power
to elected civilian government by October next year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the transition program, the government has approved
the registration of five political parties and held a local
election on party basis in March, which is generally regarded as
free and fair.
</P>
<P>
Some pro-democracy groups, however, have criticized the
government for being insincere in implementing the transition
program. They also hold that the government has not done enough
in improving its human rights records.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they have been advocating for further sanctions on
Nigeria and even for its expulsion from the Commonwealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
