<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sticks to Its Stance on U.N. Membership Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China adheres to its
principled position on the scale of assessments of the United
Nations, China's Permanent Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the Fifth Committee of the 52nd
Session of the General Assembly, he said the current scale method
on the basis of full consultations of the entire membership, is
fair and reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Such a method has basically reflected the principle of capacity
to be set forth in the Rules of Procedure of the General Assembly,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China's objection to the concept of so-called
"responsibility to pay" as it is "a proposal of money for power in
a disguised form" violating the principle of capacity to pay.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is an inter-government international organization
composed of sovereign member states, not a share-holding company
or a club of the rich, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Any proposal to base a country's role in U.N. affairs on how
much it pays runs counter to the spirit of the Organization," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Regarding a saying that China agrees to consider lowering the
scale of assessments of the largest contributor, referring to the
United States, and raising China's scale of assessments to over
four percent, Qin said "this is someone's own wishful thinking."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese delegation is of the view that adjusting the scale
of assessments involves the interests of the entire membership. It
should therefore be settled by the entire membership through
consultations on an equal and democratic basis," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"It can not and should not be determined by one or a few member
states in private," he said, adding that no country has the right
to lower its scale of assessments by itself let along willfully
demand a raise in other countries' scale of assessments," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"Any unilateral move on the question of assessments by placing
one's domestic legislation above the international community will
get nowhere," Qin went on to say.
</P>
<P>
However, He said, China does not take exception to appropriate
adjustments to the scale of assessments of member states for the
next three years on the basis of the principle of capacity to pay.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country, China needs several decades more to
catch up with the moderately developed countries even if it
maintains its current economic growth rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The attempt to drastically increase overnight China's
assessments or even redouble it in disregard of objective facts
and the principle of capacity to pay is entirely unacceptable to
the Chinese Government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the only effective way to solve the current U.N.
financial crisis is to pay up without delay the arrears by the
largest U.N. dues contributor.
</P>
<P>
"Attributing the crisis to the scale of assessments by certain
member states is ill-founded and is just an excuse for not
fulfilling financial obligations to the Organization," he pointed
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
