<HEADLINE> Russia Foreign Trade at Over 109 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia foreign trade volume
reached 109.2 billion US dollars in the first nine months, down
1.1 percent from the same period of 1996, the Interfax news agency
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax cited the State Statistics Committee as saying,
exports fell 2.2 percent to 62.3 billion US dollars, while imports
rose 0.5 percent to 46.9 billion to produce a surplus for the
period of 15.4 billion US dollars (compared with a surplus of 17
billion in the first nine months of 1996).
</P>
<P>
It said that trade with the Commonwealth Independent States
came to 25 billion US dollars, down 7.2 percent from
January-September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the CIS fell 0.8 percent to 12.7 billion, and
imports fell 12.9 percent to 12.3 billion US dollars. There was a
surplus of 0.4 billion US dollar, compared with a deficit of 1.3
billion US dollars a year ago, in trade with the CIS, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Trade with the rest of the world totaled 84.2 billion US
dollars, up 0.9 percent in the same period of last year. Exports
fell 2.6 percent to 49.6 billion US dollars, but imports grew 6.3
percent to 34.6 billion US dollars to produce a surplus of 15
billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
