<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabbah Hails Pact for His Return to Power as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Sierra Leonean President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah today reacted to the agreement signed last
week for his return to power by April next year, saying its
intention is honorable.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted him as saying at a news
conference in Edinburgh, Scotland, that his strategy is to "first
go home, work on a program of a good security system and
disarmament so that everybody can feel secure".
</P>
<P>
Kabbah is in Edinburgh to attend the Commonwealth summit of
heads of government, which closed today.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that he is yet to be briefed on the accord signed
in Conakry, Guinea, between the military authority now in
Freetown and the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
"I think the intentions of the agreement are very honorable,"
said Kabbah, "My impression is that they are trying to first get
rid of the arms and weapons in the country by encamping the
people who have them and disarming them before it will be safe
for me to resume my duties."
</P>
<P>
Kabbah also said that after the summit, he is going to
Brussels to ask the European Union for a program of assistance to
rehabilitate and rebuild his country.
</P>
<P>
Elected only in March last year, Kabbah was overthrown in a
military coup on May 25. The international society has been
demanding he be reinstated to power.
</P>
<P>
Major Johnny Kromah, who came to power after the coup,
announced previously that he is not ready to quit before the year
2001. This led to the breakdown of the first round of
negotiations between him and ECOWAS in Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Last week's agreement came after a global oil and arms embargo
on Sierra Leone by the United Nations and continuous clashes
between Kromah's soldiers and the west African intervention
forces which have been in Freetown immediately after the coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
