<HEADLINE> Kuwait Hopes for Improved Ties with Tunisia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's First Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah today
described Kuwait's ties with Tunisia as "good and progressing" and
hoped for more improvement in the future.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Sabah was speaking in an interview after meeting with
Tunisian International Cooperation and Foreign Investments
Minister Mohammad Ghannouchi who arrived here Saturday on a
four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that he was fully satisfied with the
"progress of Kuwaiti-Tunisian relations" and that Ghannouchi's
visit "helped boosts all domains of economic, investment and
development cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today a Kuwaiti Airways Corp. airplane landed in Tunis
for the first time in seven years, resuming air links between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries soured after Tunisia was
accused of having sided with Iraq during the seven-month Iraqi
occupation of the emirate and the Gulf War in 1991. But recent
years saw a full normalization of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has invested about 250 million dollars in Tunisia's
tourism sector. Its exports to the African state grew by half from
1994 to 1996 to reach 3 million dinars (9.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Tunisian exports to Kuwait climbed to nearly 6.4
million dollars last year from slightly over 1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Tunisian minister said Sunday that the two
countries would sign an accord to encourage and protect
investments.
</P>
<P>
"Tunisia seeks to encourage more Kuwaiti investments to include
other sectors of industry, agriculture, services and tourism,"
Ghannouchi said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that his visit would give an impetus to
cooperation and improved relations, as well as opening new
spheres through signing the investment protection agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
