<HEADLINE> C. African States Urged to Settle Issues Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo Dos
Santos today called on central African countries to settle
regional issues through dialogue and consultations in a bid to
find an immediate and lasting resolution.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here during a summit with his counterparts
from Gabon, the Democratic Republic of Congo and the Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
According to Dos Santos, some central African countries seemed
to have been turned into a stage for launching destructive wars,
with their people suffering and economies severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted, some countries have been used in the
interests of other nations as tools for creating instability and
chaos.
</P>
<P>
The president cited the power change in former Zaire as the
beginning of a new era for peace, regional stability and
cooperation, during which countries will collaborate in solving
problems facing them.
</P>
<P>
Central Africa has at present come to a turning point, he
said, urging all countries in the region to boost multi-lateral
cooperation within the framework of the Economic Community of
Central African States (CEEAC) and regional security system.
</P>
<P>
CEEAC should become a major bridge linking up southern Africa,
eastern Africa and western Africa in order to establish a common
market in Africa, said the Angolan head of state.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos appealed to central African nations to take up five
measures, namely a good neighborly cooperative relation, a
collective security system; a regional cooperative system and
legislation to make full use of natural resources in a bid to
turn the region into a new center for social and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The measures also include the establishment of democracy and
let it become a way to solve social, economic and cultural issues
and regular meeting between regional leaders to avoid conflicts
and promote peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The three other presidents arrived in Luanda today at the
invitation of Dos Santos. The summit will mainly discuss the
impact of drastic changes in the Democratic Congo and Congo
Brazzaville on the region so as to achieve regional stability and
to enhance its economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
