<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North-South Research Coop Vital to African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-president
Omar Ali Juma has urged developed countries to support research
activities in higher learning institutions in Africa to ensure
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Opening the African-Norwegian Universities' Conference in Dar
es Salaam today, Juma said universities in the developing
countries lack funds to conduct research.
</P>
<P>
"If we are to ensure sustainable economic development and
political stability in Africa, we must put emphasis on research,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Juma cited the key areas needing research, such as economic
reforms, poverty alleviation, agricultural production and animal
husbandry, environmental protection and control of religious and
ethnic conflicts which threaten democracy.
</P>
<P>
The vice president told the conference that inadequate funding
and material incentives have prompted many African scientists to
leave for developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"This brain drain puts us into a vicious cycle of poverty
since African countries cannot record significant economic
development without effective introduction of science and
technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the vice president called on intellectuals
not to run away from their motherland, saying that "Africa will
be built by Africans themselves."
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania will raise budgetary allocation for research
activities if the financial situation improves.
</P>
<P>
"Africa needs the support of the developed countries like
Norway in conducting serious research into effective and
sustainable approaches to economic reforms," Juma noted.
</P>
<P>
He told over 110 delegates from 25 higher learning
institutions in Africa that another area that merits the
North-South cooperation in research is poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Juma also called for greater cooperation in agricultural
production and animal husbandry, saying productivity is low and
the marketing skills in this sector is poor.
</P>
<P>
He said there is also need to carry out serious research on
livestock keeping, including the fight against persisting
diseases like trypanomysis, rinderpest and foot and mouth
diseases.
</P>
<P>
On environmental protection, the vice president called for
urgent research in seeking viable alternative sources of energy
and building materials.
</P>
<P>
Land erosion is another serious problem needing research, he
said, adding that a great part of the continent is rapidly
turning to desert because of massive tree cutting for firewood
and building.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to developed countries to support research on
conflict management, saying peace is a prerequisite for economic
development and yet it remained elusive in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
