<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-27 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Propose Open-Ended Talks on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's special advisor for Cyprus will visit the island next
month to examine whether the two Cypriot sides are ready for
open-ended talks to settle the Cyprus question.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed today by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
in Edinburgh, Britain where he is taking part in the Commonwealth
summit which concluded today, according to Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Clerides revealed that the U.N. chief had sent letters to
him, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash and the governments of
Greece and Turkey concerning this issue.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Annan said his advisor Diego Cordovez will
visit Cyprus "to see whether the two sides are willing to start
open-ended talks to solve the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
Cordovez's visit was also confirmed here today by
U.N. Resident Representative to Cyprus Gustave Feissel in his
statements at the Larnaca Airport on his return from New York,
where he conferred with Annan on the latest developments in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Feiseel said that Annan suggested in his letter a visit by
Cordovez during the second half of November to Cyprus, and also
to Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Feissel refrained from giving details about his meetings in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of Cyprus peace talks, sponsored by Cordovez, took
place this summer in the U.S. and Switzerland, which reached a
deadlock because of the Turkish Cypriot side's refusal to
negotiate unless the European Union withholds its decision to
start accession talks with Cyprus next spring.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island following
a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
