<HEADLINE> Zambia's Privatization on Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's privatization process
is on course, Jazzman Chikwakwa, Deputy Minister of Commerce,
Trade and Industry said today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day workshop for the Africa Privatization
Network here, Chikwakwa said the government is to complete
privatization, which was started soon after the current ruling
party won the country's first multi-party elections in 1991.
</P>
<P>
This must not mean that the government will be completely
de-linked from the business community and it will continue to
play its vital role of being a facilitator by ensuring that the
environment is conducive for investment, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 11 African countries are participating in
the workshop on how to promote cooperation in implementation of
the privatization programs of the countries.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO) country
director Niels Biering said on the occasion that it is important
for the countries to come together to give their experiences so
that they can learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
Privatization should not be performed in a vacuum for the mere
purpose of divesting public assets because the winds of change
are blowing in that direction, he said.
</P>
<P>
He praised the Zambia Privatization Agency for transparency
and accountability in its work.
</P>
<P>
Africa Privatization Network chairman Hamza Zayyad called on
the member countries to give finance support to the organization
and urged non-member African countries to join the network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
