<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Commonwealth's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today welcomed the
support of the Commonwealth to the demilitarization of Cyprus and
its condemnation of Turkey's threats to the east Mediterranean
island republic.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied because it reconfirms U.N. Security Council
resolutions which call for a single sovereignty and state in
Cyprus," said Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides in Edinburgh,
where he was attending a four-day Commonwealth summit.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cyprus News Agency, the president said he was
also content that the Commonwealth condemned "the bogus state in
the occupied areas and demand the withdrawal of foreign troops" in
its final communique.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus"
declared by Turkish Cypriots and recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The president said that in the communique the 54 Commonwealth
leaders adopt his proposal to demilitarize Cyprus and condemn
Turkish threats to partially annex occupied areas.
</P>
<P>
Turkey landed troops and took over the northern third of the
island in 1974 following a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
With 35,000 troops stationing there, Ankara has threatened to
partially annex the island if the European Union starts accession
talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In their five-page final communique, passed today in Edinburgh
at the end of the four-day summit, Commonwealth government leaders
reaffirmed their support for the sovereignty, independence,
territorial integrity, and unity of the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
They strongly supported the process of direct intercommunal
talks.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides expected that the Commonwealth will involve
itself in the Cyprus peace efforts if negotiations between the two
Cypriot sides take place.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Secretary-General Chief Emeka Anyaoku has
appointed as special envoy for Cyprus Krishnan Srinivasan, a
deputy secretary-general of Commonwealth for political affairs and
former Indian foreign minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
