<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Existing Home Sales Up to Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned
homes in the U.S. increased by 0.2 percent to a record high in
September, the U.S. National Association of Realtors said today.
</P>
<P>
The home trade group said that existing home sales increased to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4.32 million units, up from a
revised 4.31 million in August,
</P>
<P>
It was the highest level since the group began tracking sales
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales of existing homes jumped by 11.7 percent in
the Northeast. They were unchanged in the South. But sales dropped
by 2.8 percent in the Midwest and 4.1 percent in the West.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that strong economic growth and plentiful jobs
are giving Americans the wherewithal to buy homes. The favorite
mortgage rates, which are near the low point for the year, have
also made homes more affordable.
</P>
<P>
The group also reported that the median price of an existing
home in the nation, meaning half sold for more and half for less,
was 125,600 dollars in September, up 6.6 percent from a year
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
