<HEADLINE> Yemen to Attend Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Yemen announced today that it
will participate in the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
economic summit scheduled for next month in the Qatari capital
Doha.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh made the
announcement here at a press conference. He said Yemen will send a
low-level delegation to the meeting in protest of Israel's
hardline policy in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Radio Jordan, however, Saleh expressed Yemen's
readiness to be represented by a high-level delegation if progress
was made in the peace process. The Yemeni president was on a
two-day visit to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Saleh listed an Israeli halt of Jewish settlement activities or
further troop redeployments in West Bank as examples of progress.
</P>
<P>
Yemen became the third Arab country after Oman and Jordan to
officially declare readiness to attend the controversial
conference which traditionally included Arab states, Israel and
their major partners from the world over.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries have made their participation conditional
on possible progress in the Middle East peace process and
refrained from jumping to a final decision. 
</P>
