<HEADLINE> HK Stock Market Fall Called Short-Term Phenomenon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The recent severe downturn in
the Hong Kong stock market is a short-term phenomenon and would
not affect the long-term sentiment of investment in Asia, Hong
Kong Stock Exchange (HKSE) Chairman Edgar Cheng said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that the Hong Kong authorities have the
resources and skill to fend off the speculators," Cheng told an
international business conference.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index has plummeted nearly 6,000 points, or
one-third since the financial trouble started on October 17, the
10th anniversary of the Black Monday collapse.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were hit hard as the monetary authority jacked up
interest rates to record levels to fend off speculative attacks on
the Hong Kong dollar's peg to the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The stock market suffered its biggest loss today in terms of
points, plunging 1,428 points to close just above 9,000.
</P>
<P>
Cheng told the International Investment Funds Association
Conference that "the short-term pain which this is inflicting on
equity investors and the property market is a price worth paying
for the long-term stability of our system."
</P>
<P>
"When the attacks are seen to have failed, the present risk
premium on Hong Kong dollar interest rates will drop and the
recent panic by investors will be recognized as having been an
over-reaction," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I do believe it will take a while for investors to digest the
shock they have received in the last few months," he said. "I do
not believe, however, that recent market turmoil will alter the
long-term trend of increasing investment in Asia by global
investors."
</P>
<P>
Cheng, who will retire from his position in two days' time,
predicted that the demand for capital from regional issuers would
certainly not diminish, especially from inland areas of China. He
is optimistic that the Hong Kong market capitalization would
double again in the next five years to exceed 1 trillion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The HKSE chairman stressed that the market systems have
withstood recent dramatic swings in stock prices and heavy trading
volume without any sign of strain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the HKSE said in a statement today that it has been
monitoring the market closely from a risk management point of view
and that the market is operating in an orderly manner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
