<HEADLINE> Qatar Sees Doha Conference as "New Impetus" to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Qatar saw next month's
Middle East and North Africa (MENA) economic conference as "a new
impetus" to the stalled Arab-Israeli peace talks, Qatari Foreign
Ministry spokesman was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The conference to be held in the Qatari capital of Doha on
November 16-18 will "add a new impetus to the Middle East peace
process and advance economic development in the region," Qatari
news agency quoted Fawaz Al Attiya, spokesman of the Qatari
Foreign Ministry, as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country's determination to convene the
conference which was opposed by some Arab states due to Israel's
participation should not be regarded as a sign for its stand
change in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Qatar understands the motivation of the countries which will
attend the conference as well as the states who have decided to
boycott it," Attiya said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no difference with our (Arab brothers) on the means
but perhaps on the methods" of promoting the peace talks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are all agreed on one point: Israel must halt its policy
of building settlements in the Arab lands, abstain from
provocation, respect its commitments to peace and resume
negotiations with Syria," he added.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
talks, Syria, Lebanon, the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia
have threatened to boycott the conference which is traditionally
attended by Arab states, Israel and their major partners in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure, Qatar has downgraded the conference,
the fourth since it was launched in 1994, from a summit to a
ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Qatar said it had sent invitations to 92 countries in the
world and so far, more than 50 countries from Europe, Asia and
America have signed up their participation.
</P>
<P>
Doha said that among the countries, the United States,
European countries and Israel will sent delegations at the
ministerial level. Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will represent their
countries in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Jordan, Yemen and Oman are the only
Arab countries which have confirmed their appearance in the
three-day conference while the others remain hesitant to say
whether they would attend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
