<HEADLINE> GCC Invests Heavily in Non-oil Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) invested 77.8 billion U.S. dollars in
non-oil industries in 1996, up nearly a quarter from 1975.
</P>
<P>
This figure was released today by the regional organization in
a report at the Forum on Investment in Gulf Economic Communities
which is being held here.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, which groups Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar and Oman, has nearly 45 percent of world's
proven oil reserves and are world's major oil producers and
exporters.
</P>
<P>
Their economy depends heavily on oil revenues which account for
more than two thirds of their total income each year. From late
1980s, they pushed ahead with a drive to diversify their
oil-reliant economy.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of investments in non-oil sectors, the
countries have set up more than 6,000 industrial enterprises,
including 20 major joint ventures worth about 2.7 billion dollars,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
This strategic move has, over the past two decades, doubled the
share of the manufacturing sector in their gross domestic product
to some 9.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
