<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature:  A Milestone in Taming of China's Longest Rivers(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI (HENAN), October 28 (Xinhua) -- Though the Yangtze
River and the Yellow River have long been considered symbols of
the Chinese nation, never before have the country's two longest
waterways attracted as much attention as they did today.
</P>
<P>
The flood-prone Yellow River, which has repeatedly wreaked
havoc throughout China's 2,500 years of recorded history, changed
its course forever at 10:28 a.m. today, when the last load of
stone sealed the opening of a multi-purpose dam at Xiaolangdi, 40
km northwest of Luoyang, an ancient city in central China's Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts have hailed today's completion of the damming of the
Xiaolangdi Multi-Purpose Water Control Project, the largest of its
kind on the Yellow River, as a success.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, work to narrow the gap of a coffer dam at Sandouping
as part of the construction of the Three Gorges Project is
proceeding smoothly. One after the other, heavy-duty trucks
shuttled between the dam and the stone-pit round-the-clock to dump
boulders into the river. Ten days from now, China's longest river
will be dammed by the world's largest dam.
</P>
<P>
Both rivers originate from the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and flow
east, with the Yangtze River passing through provinces in Southern
China, and the Yellow River stretching across Northern China. To
dam the two rivers in 10 days is an extraordinary undertaking
in a showdown with Mother Nature, and adds lustre to the already
eventful year of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though the two massive water control projects are expected to
be completed early next century, the closing of the dams marked
that the two highly challenging projects have achieved
considerable progress.
</P>
<P>
Builders described the two projects as milestones in the
history of water control in China.
</P>
<P>
Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources, said the river
damming marks the beginning of a new phase in harnessing the two
hazardous rivers.
</P>
<P>
Xiaolangdi is regarded as one of the most complex engineering
jobs ever in history, due to its complex geographical features and
high containment of sediment in water. The successful damming of
the river indicates that the toughest technical problems in
construction have been solved. The key task now is to heighten the
dam to a crest of 154 meters.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project will enter the phase of dam and power
house building after closing of the coffer dam on November 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature:  A Milestone in Taming of China's Longest Rivers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese have mixed feelings about the Yangtze and Yellow
Rivers, which have been dubbed both "the cradle of Chinese
civilization" and "the sorrow of the Chinese nation."
</P>
<P>
The two rivers have produced catastrophic floods every other
year in the 2,000 years prior to the founding of New China in
1949. The Yellow River recorded a disastrous breach in 1938,
killing more than 900,000. A powerful flood which occurred at the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River in 1954 resulted in
30,000 deaths and inundated over three million ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
But taming the Yangtze and Yellow rivers was just wishful
thinking for centuries.
</P>
<P>
In the past four decades and more, the government has built a
big number of water control projects on the two rivers. Sanmenxia
Reservoir and Gezhouba Water Control Project were among the most
successful.
</P>
<P>
Pan Jiazheng, an established Chinese hydraulician, said that
the building of the Three Gorges Project and Xiaolangdi Water
Control Project is a turning point in harnessing the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
No other projects can match the two massive schemes, Pan said,
as the Three Gorges Project will raise the flood prevention
capacity along the river from the current once per 10 years to
once per 100 years for the occurrence of major floods. The
Xiaolangdi Project will raise flood prevention capacity from the
present 60 years to 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, experts warned that serious hidden troubles
caused by floods still exist. The riverbed at the lower
reaches of the Yellow River, the world's muddiest, rises 10 cm
annually due to silting. The river has become a "hanging river,"
with the riverbed perched 20 meters above cities on both banks.
</P>
<P>
Of the Yellow River drainage basin, 694,000 sq. km or 93
percent, is located upstream from the Xiaolangdi site, putting
Xiaolangdi in a key position to control flooding and sedimentation
of the river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: A Milestone in Taming of China's Longest Rivers (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Three Gorges and Xiaolangdi projects are trans-century
endeavors designed to benefit future generations. They are not
only to serve as flood control facilities to protect the highest
area of farmland and the most people, but also will provide huge
amounts of water and power resources for the development of the
Yangtze and Yellow rivers areas. The two projects will also play a
big role in improving the environment and eco-system.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion in 2009, the Three Gorges hydropower station
will be the world's largest, equipped with a capacity of 18.2
million KW. The equivalent of a tenth of the country's total
electricity at present will go to east China, central China, and
Chongqing municipality, which contribute 40 percent to China's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Electricity generated by the Three Gorges power plant is equal
that of 10 thermal power plants each with a capacity of 1.8
million KW. Thus, the plant will alleviate the logistics problems
of transporting and consuming 50 million tons of coal annually,
and will greatly reduce environmental pollution along the Yangtze
River watershed.
</P>
<P>
The project will make it possible for 10,000-ton freighters to
go directly to Chongqing, and markedly improve China's "golden
passage", the Yangtze River, which accounts for 80 percent of
country's waterway transport through inland rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi project is expected to increase enough water
resources to cover 2.2 million ha of farmland in Shangdong and
Henan provinces, and to yield a million tons of grain and 58,000
tons of cotton annually. It will also provide water for Beijing,
Tianjin, and some other cities which face water supply shortages.
</P>
<P>
"The two projects can match any project of the kind in the rest
of the world, in terms of scale, technology, and economic
results," said Pan Jiazheng, an academician of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: A Milestone in Taming of China's Longest Rivers (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prof. Zhang Guangdou of Qinghua University was strongly opposed
to the building of the Three Gorges project in the 1940s. But now
the 85-year-old authority on China's water conservation and
hydropower is a staunch advocate.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, China's economic and financial conditions
couldn't afford such a gigantic project as the Three Gorges
project. But now China is rapidly gaining national strength, with
equally fast development of science and technology, and the
national economy need more power. That's why I say 'Yes' to the
project," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project cost 6.5 billion yuan in 1995,
accounting for 0.11 percent of GDP, a striking contrast to bygone
days when the country had to scrape to fund even a minor project.
</P>
<P>
The two endeavors are not only a symbol of overall national
strength, but also direct results of the reform and opening-up
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Without the reform and opening-up drive, projects like these
would be inconceivable," said Zhang Jiyao, vice-minister of Water
Resources, who is in charge of the Xiaolangdi project.
</P>
<P>
The first large project to be run according to
internationally-accepted practices, Xiaolangdi used more than a
billion US dollars in loans, and was open to worldwide
bidding. Consequently, the construction work of the dam, the flood
diversion project, and the power-generation project went to some
multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
Of the more than 10,000 builders on Xiaolangdi, over 700
experts and technicians came from some 50 countries and regions,
prompting some observers to call the construction site a
"mini-United Nations".
</P>
<P>
"Open the door for the construction of the Three Gorges
project" is the comment on international cooperation by Lu Youmei,
general manager of the Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development
Corp, which overally takes care of the project.
</P>
<P>
Diverse forms of funding were used in China and overseas to
raise money for the 200-plus-billion-yuan project, with key
generators and other equipment imported from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Despite this fruitful year of 1997 for China's water
conservation, Chinese water control experts remain
sober-minded. As Prof. Pan put it, "we cannot expect to finish our
work with the two projects once for all. In fact, we still have a
long way to go in harnessing the Yangtze and Yellow rivers."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Institutes: Unemployment Continue to Rise in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's six leading economic
institutes today predicted that the country's unemployment would
continue to rise next year, reaching an average of 4.42 million, up
from this year's 4.38 million.
</P>
<P>
In a joint autumn report on German economy published today, they
said high joblessness would remain a major concern to the government
and a turnabout on the job market is "not in sight."
</P>
<P>
They criticized the political sector for failure to carry out tax
reforms this year, which they said had reduced "the readiness of
companies to expand their capacities or to hire additional labor."
</P>
<P>
The institutes forecast that the country's economy would grow by
2.4 percent this year and 2.8 percent in 1998, slightly faster than
earlier estimation.
</P>
<P>
In the biennial joint report presented to Bonn, they also warned
that for the first time since 1990 reunificaton, overall economic
output in eastern Germany would grow slower than in western part of
the country in 1998 due to dropping construction investments.
</P>
<P>
The six independent institutes are located in Berlin, Munich,
Hamburg, Kiel, Magdeburg and Essen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
