<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Debate Links Between Traditional Culture and Modern Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- What's the connection between
traditional Chinese culture and modern management? Can the Chinese
people use the wisdom of traditional culture to go about the market
economy in the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
These were some of the questions debated by more than 120
renowned scholars and enterpreneurs from China and overseas during
an international symposium, which closed today in Ningbo, east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Participants from Chinese interior area, Hong Kong and Taiwan,
and those from foreign countries, including Japan, the Untied
States, and Singapore discussed "the role of traditional Chinese
culture in market economy," "traditional culture and modern
enterprise management" and other issues during the three-day
symposium, jointly sponsored by the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences and the Ningbo City Government.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the rapid economic growth of Japan, Thailand,
the Republic of Korea, Singapore, China's interior area and Taiwan
in the 1970s and 1980s has been influenced by traditional Chinese
culture.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese economists spoke on the current economic situation
in China, pointing out that the Chinese economy has entered a
stable and gradually progressing period, with a growth rate of
nine percent and an inflation rate of two percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
