<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish Public Doubt Joining EMU in First Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 59 percent of the Finnish
people are opposed to joining the European Monetary Union (EMU) in
the first wave, a recent survey conducted by the Council of the
Finnish Economic Circle revealed.
</P>
<P>
Although 80 percent of the Finnish people believe the country
will join the EMU in the first wave as the government has
proposed, most of them are in doubt about the move. The doubts
were instigated by the prudent attitudes of Britain and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Finland was the first group of European Union (EU) member
countries to meet the criteria for joining the EMU. Its government
has been actively preparing for entry into the European
integration system in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
However, the biggest opposition party, the Finnish Centre and
some other parties, strongly oppose joining the EMU in the first
wave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
