<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia for Resuming Peace Talks on All Tracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia is pressing for the
resumption of Middle East peace talks on all tracks, visiting
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said here today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark after meeting separately with Jordan's Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali and Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Russia calls for reviving the peace negotiations on all tracks
involving Israel, the Palestinians, Lebanon and Syria, said
Primakov, who arrived here last night on a two-day working visit
to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He described Jordan's role in the peace process as "vital" and
said Russia would like to develop its relations with the kingdom
for the benefit of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth leg of his Middle East tour in a bid to
reactivate Russia's role as a co-sponsor of the peace-making
between the Arabs and Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Primakov, Majali reiterated the kingdom's
position and strong conviction that the peace process would not
continue if it did not include all tracks.
</P>
<P>
He deemed Israeli government`s stand on the peace process as
"unreasonable and unacceptable." There would not be security and
peace without restoring the lands and rights to the Arabs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Majali rejected Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu`s
demand to give priority to security over peace, insisting that
security could only be achieved through peace.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh told Primakov that peace was a strategic option for
the Arab countries, and stressed Jordan`s commitment to secure
progress on various tracks and revive a comprehensive peace in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Later in the afternoon Primakov started a closed-door meeting
with King Hussein in the Royal Palace.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's week-long trip in the region began on October 24 in
Lebanon, which also includes Syria, Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule area, Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Although Russia co-sponsored the peace process together with
the U.S., its long absence in the region has left Washington
played the dominant role in brokering talks between the Arabs and
Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
