<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Awaits Guidelines for Talks with Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said today he is still not sure if he will travel to
the United States for talks with Palestinian deputy leader Mahmoud
Abbas (Abu Mazen).
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with a delegation of the European
Parliament, Levy said he is still waiting for a meeting of the
inner cabinet, to be convened tomorrow, to formulate guidelines
for future negotiations with the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
If the parameters for concessions that Israel is expected to
make and the commitments to be undertaken by the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) are defined, Levy will be able to leave
for Washington in time for talks to begin early next week.
</P>
<P>
But the possibility of delay caused by ministerial wrangling
over security concerns and other issues could push the diplomatic
timetable back to the point where a trilateral session will not be
feasible until late November or early December.
</P>
<P>
This is because U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
scheduled to attend the World Economic Forum's Middle East and
North Africa economic conference due to open in Doha, capital of
Qatar on November 16.
</P>
<P>
Levy conferred with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Monday on
three main issues which he wants specific instructions: a
"time-out" on settlement activity; further redeployment of Israeli
troops in the West Bank and preparations for the final status
talks.
</P>
<P>
Levy was said to be pleased with the outcome of his dialogue
with Netanyahu. "We discussed several ideas," Levy said, "I hope
that they will be crystallized in final form by the end of
(tomorrow's) Cabinet meeting. When they are adopted, we will be
able to convene the meeting in Washington in a manner that will be
fruitful and will inject momentum into the peace process."
</P>
<P>
On Palestinian side, PNA President Yasser Arafat said Monday
that the PNA was withholding a decision about whether to attend
next week's planned talks in Washington until Israel decides.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait for the final resolution from the Israeli side
to decide if we will go to this meeting or not," Arafat
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
