conferring intensively, responded to the Wall Street stock
market plunge with little more than soothing words about the
underlying strength of the U.S. Economy.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Stocks plummeted as a continuing sell-off eliminated about
$1.2 trillion in global market value. Trading in the U.S. was
halted early for the first time under the Big Board's
circuit-breaker rules after the Dow Jones industrials sand
554.26, or 7.18%, to 7161.15. It was the Dow's biggest point
drop ever, while only the 12th worst in percentage terms.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks were sharply lower midday Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Latin American stocks were among the hardest hit, amid fears
that the turmoil in southeast Asia might roil current markets
there next.
</P>
<P>
Economists say ties between business and markets are tested
by plunge in stocks. 
