<HEADLINE> Kuwait Plans to Adopt Foreign Investment Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti government
will soon submit to the National Assembly a draft law aimed at
encouraging foreign investment in the country, the Kuwaiti prime
minister told the parliament today.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Sabah made the remarks in a speech televised and broadcast
live at the parliament which opened its second session today
after a three-month summer recess.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad said "a draft law will soon be submitted to the
assembly that aims at encouraging foreign investment in Kuwait
and benefiting from up-to-date foreign expertise and technology
and qualification of national cadres."
</P>
<P>
He said his government "has adopted a number of new projects
to realize improvement in the planned development process, to
expose its dimensions, define its goals and evaluate its
achievements."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said a special ministerial committee has
been set up to follow the implementation of the government
program and make an appraisal report on various sectors in order
to fulfill national strategic objectives.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, he said the Kuwaiti
government emphasizes the importance of the implementation of
international legitimacy resolutions and the land for peace
principle, stressing the need to restart the peace negotiations
on all tracks to attain just, comprehensive and everlasting
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait would also make further efforts to rejuvenate
the Damascus Declaration and reasserts its belief in the Arab
League charter as well as joint Arab action in the manner that
serves the common Arab cause.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Speaker of the National Assembly Ahmed Abdul Azziz
Al-Sadoun said at the session that it would discuss a host of
bills relating to important issues as well as other matters
proposed by the parliamentary committees.
</P>
<P>
He said the parliament is always ready to adopt suitable
positions on different international issues, to boost ties with
the brothers in the Gulf region and Arab and other friendly
countries. 
</P>
