<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Dive in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The price of shares on the Seoul
stock exchange plunged sharply today to below the 500-point level,
and the U.S. dollar was unusually strong against the South Korean
won.
</P>
<P>
Amid the reported crash of foreign stock markets, in a wave of
heavy selling by panicked players throughout the session, the
leading composite index crashed as much as 35.19 point to close at
495.28.
</P>
<P>
The plunge, representing a decline of 6.63 percent, was the
largest single-day fall in the history of the South Korean bourse,
depressing the market below the 500-point mark for the first time
in more than five years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, amid rekindled dollar demand and bearish foreign
stock investors' continuously fleeing from the market, the South
Korean won continued its plunge to set another new record low
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the time of this report, foreign exchange authorities gave
up intervening in the market after its failure to keep the 940-won
resistance barrier Monday. The dollar, beginning 3.20-won higher
on Tuesday, shot up to end at 957.60 won, up as much as 21 won
over the base rate.
</P>
<P>
The base conversion rate scheduled to be posted Wednesday will
be 942.80 won to the dollar, which means the won dropped more than
3-percent this month alone and 11.8 percent from 844.20 at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
While ruling and opposition parties urged the government to
take extraordinary measures to bridge the current monetary crisis,
financial sources are concerned that the won will plunge even
further toward the end of this year before stablizing.
</P>
<P>
Despite the growing monetary jitters and the drop in foreign
exchange reserves to below 30 billion U.S. dollars, government
financial experts discount the possibility of a foreign exchange
crisis in South Korea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
