<HEADLINE> Ruling South African Party Condemns Coup in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,October 28 (Xinhua) -- The ruling African
National Congress (ANC) of South Africa has condemned the
shortlived military coup in Zambia today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the ANC said it "unequivocally condemns attempts
by a clique of military officers to use unconstitutional means to
remove from office the democratically-elected government of
Zambia".
</P>
<P>
The statement noted: "Africa can no longer tolerate undemocratic,
dictatorial and militaristic regimes being imposed upon the will
of the majority of the people any where on the continent."
</P>
<P>
It said whatever political problems may exist, such problems
should be resolved through political and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The ANC welcomed reports that the coup had failed and that
President Frederick Chiluba was still in control.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers led by Captain Solo announced the coup this morning
through radio. His sodiers surrounded the State House in Lusaka
by force.
</P>
<P>
Solo threatened that President Chiluba must surrender and
leave his office.
</P>
<P>
By 09:05 local time, Chiluba declared in Lusaka that the coup
had been aborted and the situation in the capital was firmly
under control. 
</P>
