<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Twenty-two Canadian firms are looking forward to
concluding contracts with Iraq to enter the Iraqi market within
the framework of the oil-for-food deal signed by Iraq with the
U.N..
</P>
<P>
Iraqi newspaper "Al-Jomhouriya" today quoted Michael Taylor,
chairman of the Canalac Company of Canada as saying that a number
of Canadian firms specializing in food and pharmaceutical
manufacturing, farming and veterinary medicine are willing to
cooperate and trade with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Robert Jerry, chairman of Canada's truck-producing Nadossica
Company, showed his company's readiness to supply Iraq with a
collection of trucks, as well as loading and unloading equipment
required by the process of transporting the food products brought
into Iraq in accordance with the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
It was announced in the Iraqi capital today that 45 French
firms in various sectors would participate in the 30th Baghdad
International Fair due to last ten days starting from November 1st.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that 30 Spanish firms are going to participate
in the same fair for the first time since the UN economic blockade
laid after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran earned 1.65 billion U.S. dollars from non-oil
exports during the past six months, said Ahmad Qassemi, director
of the export promotion department of the Industries Ministry.
</P>
<P>
This shows an increase of 18.1 percent, compared to that of the
same period of the last Iranian fiscal year (starting from March
21, 1996 to March 20, 1997), said Qassemi.
</P>
<P>
He said that industrial exports managed by the Industries
Ministry during the period stood at 621 million dollars, up by 21
percent compared to the figure of the same period in the last
fiscal year. Exports are expected to earn some 1.78 billion
dollars by the end of the current Iranian fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- German airline Lufthansa resumed flights to Beirut
Monday after a 14-year suspension, Lebanese newspaper Beirut Times
said.
</P>
<P>
Three weekly flights between Beirut and Frankfurt have been
scheduled for every Monday, Wednesday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The return of Lufthansa brings to 32 the number of airlines
that now operate out of Beirut's airport.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait is the second largest consuming market
for information technology after Saudi Arabia in the Gulf region,
the Director General of Kuwait's Information Center Company Mansur
Al-Mousa said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the occasion of the
inauguration of the 16th International Exhibition for Information
Technology in Kuwait, Al-Mousa said that computer software
constituted 40 percent of the total sales of information
technology market.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Kuwaiti computer market currently has 100,000 computers
and every year a total of 20,000 new computers also find their
way into the market. Kuwait was the first Gulf country to have
introduced Internet services.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mousa attributed the boom in Kuwait's information technology
market to several factors including an increase in computer usage
awareness, low prices and the widespread use of Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
