<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Worse Yet to Come in Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 28 (Xinhua) -- As regional markets tumbled,
political leaders and market analysts warned today that the
current financial crisis in Southeast Asia is likely to spill over
to the world markets and that the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, who is now in Denmark
on an official visit, said today that the turbulence in the
financial markets will not be isolated and kept to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
A local television report quoted the prime minister as saying
the contagion effect could spread to Europe and other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
What is important is to restore confidence in Southeast Asia,
he stressed, adding that the basic factors underlying the region
are still sound.
</P>
<P>
The world stock markets plunged today in a chain reaction under
the weight of Asia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Free falls in New York and Europe fueled a new round of losses
as early trading began in Asian markets today, with stock markets
in Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, New Zealand, Australia, Japan
and South Korea all going down sharply.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng index crashed through the 9,000-point floor in
Hong Kong in the morning before recovering in the afternoon to
close at 9,059.89 points, down by 1,438.31 points or 14 percent
from the previous close, suffering the largest single-day point
drop ever.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) lost
122.87 points to close at 1,497.03, hitting the lowest level in at
least five years.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the overnight sharp fall on Wall Street and the
plunge in the Hong Kong market, the STII nose-dived immediately
after trading opened. It once dropped to the 1,486.74-point level
at 3:45 p.m., down by 133.16 points from the opening of 1,619.9
points.
</P>
<P>
A well-known global strategist predicted here today that
further selling in global markets would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, there is probably more to come," said David Roche,
president and global strategist at Independent Strategy.
</P>
<P>
"Our forecast for the decline in major global equity markets
stays unchanged: a fall of 20-25 percent from the peak," he said,
adding, "That implies a further 15-percent correction from current
levels."
</P>
<P>
Roche, a bear on Asian markets, told a gathering of fund
managers here that the environment is now bullish for bonds. The
strategy is to buy long-term bonds and stay overweight in the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The global stock market correction is likely to keep the U.S.
dollar strong as a safe haven currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he also noted that the material impact of Asia's
financial crisis on the U.S. and other developed markets is small,
because the region constitutes just 8.5 percent of the world
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Discussion Urges Improvements for People's Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China's senior lawmakers called
for strengthening democratic and legal construction and further
perfecting the system of the people's congresses as the country's
fundamental political system.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, discussed the report by
Jiang Zemin at the Party's 15th national congress during the first
two days of the committee's 28th session which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's report placed more emphasis on building democracy and
the legal system in China, members said, and confirmed that
building a country under the rule of law guarantees smooth
development of various causes of the Party and the country.
</P>
<P>
Huanjue Cailang, chairman of the standing committee of the
Qinghai provincial people's congress, said that expanding
socialist democracy and improving socialist legal system feature
prominently in Jiang Zemin's report.
</P>
<P>
"This represents an important development in the way the Party
manages the country and it is the continuation and creative
development of Deng Xiaoping Theory about democracy and legal
system," Huanjue said.
</P>
<P>
NPC standing committee member Qu Geping said that China faces
the task of modernizing in the 21st century not only in economic
terms but also in political terms.
</P>
<P>
"The hallmark of a modern political system in China is a
perfected system of people's congresses," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
Many members pointed out that realizing a rule of law in China
is to guarantee that the NPC and its standing committee perform
their functions as state power organs according to law and to
enhance their role in legislation and supervision.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the Standing Committee of the Eighth National
People's Congress has made great strides in building up a legal
framework by drafting an unprecedented number of laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Members said they will act under the guidelines of the Party's
congress and continue to strengthen legislation and supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
