<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Minister Expects Oil Prices at 23 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Oil Minister Obeid bin Saif Al Nasir expected here today
that world oil prices will climb to 23 dollars in the next six
months due to increasing demands in the world.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today during the Forum On Investment In
Gulf Economic Communities held here, the UAE oil minister said he
expected that the prices for Opec's basket of seven crudes will
soar by about four dollars per barrel in the last quarter of this
year and the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
He said his prediction was based on world increasing demands
and the output decline of the non-Opec oil producers.
</P>
<P>
The increase will be mainly due to the upcoming winter in
the Northern Hemisphere, he stated.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Nasir also reiterated the UAE's commitment to
its oil output quota awarded by Opec at 2.2 million barrels
per day (bpd) and he urged other Opec members to maintain
the organization's output ceiling to shore up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The current Opec ceiling was set in September 1993 with
the exception of Iraq's. It stands at 25.03 million bpd and
remained unchanged for four years.
</P>
<P>
However, Opec's reports showed that the actual output now
is running nearly two million barrels a day in excess of the
ceiling because many members are known to have been exceeding
their quotas.
</P>
<P>
This has greatly affected crude prices which currently hover
around 19 dollars a barrel, sharply dropping from 25 dollars a
barrel in late 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Condemns Failed Military Coup in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba here today condemned the aborted military coup
and pledged to continue
economic and political reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide televised speech at the State House this
afternoon, Chiluba said the coupists are against the Zambian
people and they wanted to destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
The president said that his government will try to maintain
peace and never allow bloodshed in Zambia. He warned that no
force against the government shall ever succeed or prosper.
</P>
<P>
He called on the whole nation to work together to rebuild the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the speech, Chiluba assured the nation and investors,
both local and foreign, that his government will continue the
economic and political reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president also thanked the country's army and air force
for their loyalty to the government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, Chiluba made a speech on the state
radio, confirming that an military coup has been put down and the
situation in the capital is firmly under control.
</P>
<P>
The attempted coup was staged around 6 o'clock local time and
the coup leader Captain "Solo" has been identified by army
sources as Captain Steven Mungu.
</P>
<P>
In a radio announcement after his men besieged the State House
and took Zambia's Mass Complex, Captain Mungu demanded Chiluba to
resign or the coupists will take by force the State House where
the president lives.
</P>
<P>
Heavily-armed forces supporting the government later
surrounded the Mass Complex at noon and arrested Mungu as well as
several soldiers involved in the coup, a senior army official
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
About 10 vehicles, more military jeeps and about one hundred
government soldiers are now placed around the Mass Complex which
houses the Zambia Broadcasting Services, Zambia Information
Services and the Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no signs of tension in the streets although
all shops and government offices are closed. And no casualties
are reported during the three-hour coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
