<HEADLINE> Ghana's Leading Gold Firm Forecasts Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Ashati Goldfields, the leading
gold producer of Ghana, is expected to earn 40-50 million U.S.
Dollars this year as against the 60 million dollars recorded last
year, according to a company report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The company, which accounts for about 80 percent of the
estimated market capitalization of 1.31 billion dollars of the
Ghana Stock Exchange, recorded a 42 percent drop in its second
quarter pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
However the company said the sharp drop in profit is not
likely to affect the 1997 revenue and cost forecasts.
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, the unsatisfactory performance of the
international gold market is expected to impact negatively on the
fortune of Ashati, which is also listed in London and New York
stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
However, financial analysts say that with a cash cost of
265-269 dollars per ounce, the company can weather the downward
turn in the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the company, 80 percent of
its 1998 output is ledged at 428 dollars per ounce and more than
five million ounces at over 420 dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Gold mining is currently one of the most active industrial
sector of Ghana, while gold export has surpassed that of cocoa,
becoming the country's primary foreign exchange earner.  
</P>
