<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Encourages LDCs to Use Multilateral Trade System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) Rubens
Ricupero has called for fresh thinking in order to let the Least
Developed Countries (LDCs) utilize the multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of an inter-agency meeting on
Integrated Initiatives for LDC Trade Development on Monday,
Ricupero expressed dissatisfaction with the fact that only half
the 48 LDCs are currently members of the World Trade Organization
(WTO) and that their representation at the two-day meeting is
small.
</P>
<P>
Noting that WTO's dispute settlement procedures, which are
costly and difficult, have caused problems for LDCs in utilizing
this mechanism adequately, Ricupero said.
</P>
<P>
"Fresh thinking is needed to resolve this problem, possibly
through the provision of international judicial assistance."
</P>
<P>
The meeting on October 27-28 involves six international
institutions including WTO, UNCTAD, the International Trade Center
(ITC, a joint subsidiary of UNCTAD and WTO), the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the importance of the meeting, Ricupero said the
meeting is the first of its kind for two reasons: It is the first
meeting specifically devoted to LDCs in the context of the
WTO. Secondly, it marks a new alliance among six major
international institutions to develop a coherent and integrated
approach to LDC trade-related problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
