<HEADLINE> China's Gold Production Up Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China has reached its goal for
1997 in gold production three months ahead of schedule, according
to a recent issue of China Gold, one of the publications published
by the Ministry of Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, the country turned out 101.8 tons of
gold, up 20.3 percent over the corresponding period for last
year. The target for gold output for the whole of 1997 set by the
ministry was only 100 tons.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the ministry attributed its achievements to the
reforms and efforts of local gold-mining companies to increase
production.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold has been down in China, but the cost of gold
production has been rising due to price hikes in raw materials,
fuel and electricity. 
</P>
