<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Sales of Industrial Robots Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The global sales of industrial
robots in 1996 reached about 80,500 units, an 11 percent increase
over the previous year, the United Nations Economic Commission for
Europe (UN/ECE) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Although the year 1996 marked the second consecutive year of
double digit growth in world robot sales, the robots sold in 1996
were less than those in 1990 when they peaked at almost 81,000
units, said a UN/ECE press release.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the sales of robots in 1997 is predicted to reach at
least 10 percent, and the UN/ECE foresees a yearly average growth
of more than 15 percent in the period of 1998-2000, or sales will
increase from 80,500 units in 1996 to about 131,000 units in the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the stock of operational industrial robots
worldwide will increase from nearly 680,000 units at the end of 1996
to about 950,000 at the end of 2000, of which more than half will
be in Japan, followed by the United States with 100,000 units,
Germany's 77,000, Italy's 335,000, France's 19,000 and Britain's
12,000, the UN/ECE said.
</P>
<P>
One of the ways to calculate robot density is the number of
robots per 10,000 persons employed in the manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
Japan has so far the highest density of advanced robots. In
1996, it had 225 units (265 if counting all types of robots) per
10,000 persons engaged in manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea had the second highest with 75 units last year,
followed by Germany with 71, Sweden with 54 and Italy with 47. In
other Western European countries, Australia and the United States,
the density ranged from 15 to 40 robots per 10,000 persons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
