<HEADLINE> Tel Aviv Stock Exchange Halts Trading Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The trade in Tel Aviv Stock
Exchange was halted temporarily Tuesday morning following a
stumbling 12 percent fall in the share prices.
</P>
<P>
The trading was halted at 11:45 am Tuesday for 45 minutes after
the share prices plunged by 12 percent in panic trading, which was
caused by the Dow Jones dive in New York Stock Exchange Monday.
</P>
<P>
After it was decided to limit the decrease of stock prices to
10 percent, the trading in Tel Aviv Stock Exchange resumed at
about 12:30 pm.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government was quick to come out to calm the stock
market as Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Finance Minister
Yaakov Neeman called on the public not to be panic.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that Israeli economy
is strong and the public should be confident about the stock
market and not be panic.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel is the second most important hi-tech
market in the world after the Silicon Valley in California of the
United States, adding this should be reflected in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he did not want to advise investors what to do
at the time, but Neeman asked them to calculate their steps well.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli share market plummeted following the worldwide
drop in major stock markets, especially in Hong Kong Stock
Exchange and New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Today's drop in the share market also followed the
announcement by Bank of Israel that it would leave the interest
rate unchanged in November despite the speculation that the
interest rate would be lowered due to the negative consumer price
index in September.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street abruptly shut down 30 minutes before the closing
bell Monday, when the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 554.26
points, the largest one-day point decline ever.
</P>
<P>
Most Israeli shares traded on the New York market also
plunged, dropping an average of 6.5 percent. Israeli stocks in
Tel Aviv exchange also dropped for about 1.7 percent Monday as
investors expressed concern about continued declines in New York,
particularly Israeli companies listed on Wall Street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
