<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Calls for Further Investment Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Secretary for Trade
and Industry Denise Yue today called for further dismantling
investment barriers and enhancing the transparency of investment
regimes among Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) members.
</P>
<P>
She told the opening of a two-day APEC Investment Symposium
that attracting foreign investment is one of the top priorities of
many economies today, and the wish to attract investment has
resulted in a greater willingness to establish a more liberal
investment framework.
</P>
<P>
The trend toward liberalization notwithstanding, restrictions
still exist in many investment regimes due to historical,
economic, national security and other reasons, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
These restrictions often take the form of admission barriers,
foreign ownership control, export requirements, local content
requirements and technology transfer requirements, she added.
</P>
<P>
"We need to further dismantle these investment barriers and
enhance the transparency of investment regimes in order to be able
to realize the full benefits of liberalization," the official
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Given the turbulence in Southeast Asian financial markets in
the last couple of months, some may doubt whether free flow of
investment is all that good. "Some will point to the havoc
purportedly wreaked on regional financial markets by overseas
investors as proof that investment and liberalization bring with
them disbenefits," Yue said.
</P>
<P>
However, she stressed, these recent problems actually
reinforce, and not weaken, the arguments for a stable investment
environment and a robust investment regime.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, the third of its kind, was hosted by the
Industry Department of the Hong Kong SAR government. The overall
theme this year is enhancing the environment for investment in
APEC, which underlines the vital importance of investment in the
process of economic development in the APEC economies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
