 creation of such a significant new trade event creates many
opportunities for buyers and sellers in the hardware business.
</P>
<P>
Liang said that hardware products are important to Hong Kong's
trade. In 1996, Hong Kong exported 24.9 billion HK dollars (3.19
billion U.S. dollars) of traditional hardware items, such as hand
tools, metal parts, wiring nails, nuts and screws to all parts of
the world.
</P>
<P>
This fair has attracted 170 exhibitors from Hong Kong, China's
inland and other countries and regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
Among the major product categories are do-it-yourself products,
tools and equipment, gardening and camping gear, auto and home
improvement items.
</P>
<P>
"Hardware traders should also take advantage of the prevalent
Asian moving trends towards higher urbanization, more and smaller
household units and improved transport, power and communication
services," Liang said.
</P>
<P>
Everything -- from the construction of massive power projects,
bridges and highways to more families moving into new flats --
tends to trigger demand for quality hardware items, large and
small, he added.
</P>
<P>
Frederick Lam, deputy executive director of the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (HKTDC), said at the opening ceremony that new
trade fairs, like this one, demonstrate not only that the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) is conducting business as
usual, but that Hong Kong's appetite and scope for business
continues to expand.
</P>
<P>
As the organizer, HKTDC is proud to play a role in bringing so
many buyers and sellers together in a setting and circumstances
bound to facilitate business deals, Lam said.  
</P>
