<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aborted Coup in Zambia Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States ambassador to
the United Nations Bill Richardson today condemned the coup
attempt in Zambia this morning before he left Kenya, a stop of
his current six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Richardson said: "We are always
concerned about undemocratic, unconstitutional overthrows of
elected governments," according to a report from Nairobi available
here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Regional Superintendent of the Church of God,
Bishop John Manbo, also condemned here the coup attempt, saying
violence not the answer to the country's problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the public should not just rejoice that the coup has
been foiled but should pray for peace to continue.
</P>
<P>
He urged Zambian President Frederick Chiluba to be magnanimous
enough to call for round table talks with all stakeholders
including the church, opposition parties and trade unions to find
a solution to the outstanding national issues.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the president needs to hear from all
stakeholders what is the grievance in the nation because his
advisors could not tell him the unpleasant truth.
</P>
<P>
He also cautioned former president Kenneth Kaunda, arch rival
of Chiluba, against making inflammatory public remarks, adding
that he would have been accused of having connections with the
plotters, had the coup succeeded.
</P>
<P>
One of Kaunda's supporters said that although he is opposed to
Chiluba, he is happy at the news that the coup has been foiled
because Zambians do not want to be led by a military regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
