<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa on HK Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KOGN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
said that today's share falls at the Hong Kong stock market was a
reaction to that around the world, urging local citizens not to
panic.
</P>
<P>
After today's Executive Council meeting, Tung told reporters
that he thinks "the market still goes up and down" and "the latest
 round is due to what happened overseas."
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index plunged 15.5 percent on selling this
morning, with 1,627.70 points down through the 9,000 point barrier
 for the first time in 26 months to hit 8,870. 5 in late morning
trade, in the wake of an overnight global market crash.
</P>
<P>
The dive followed a 7.18 percent fall on Wall Street overnight,
which in turn stemmed from Monday's 5.8 percent decline here as
the SAR government sought to defend the Hong Kong dollar and its
peg to the U.S. dollar from speculators' attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index fell 1,438.31 points, or 13.70 percent, to
close at 9,059.89 after a slight recovery in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Questioned by reporters, Tung said: "Well, I think the market
still goes up and down. What has happened this morning was a
reaction to what happened around the world, particularly in New
York, and from our side we don't see any panic."
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals here are very good, the economy is going well
in Hong Kong and the economy in China is going very well," the
Chief Executive said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the peg of the linked exchange rate is
staying and it is slowly but surely coming to normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
