<HEADLINE> French Rhone-Poulenc Opens Technology Park in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The French chemical and
pharmaceutical conglomerate Rhone-Poulenc has opened the first
phase of its technology park in Shanghai, China's largest
industrial and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Cost of the first phase is 24 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The multi-purpose Technology Park in the Shanghai Shenzhuang
Industrial Zone is the first of its kind in China's chemical and
pharmaceutical industries.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, which involves a high-technology silicon
manufacturing plant and four chemical applications laboratories,
has a floor space of 10 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Marc Bruel, vice-chairman of the Rhone-Poulenc Group, said
that construction of the technology park was a concrete example of
Rhone-Poulenc's determination to be a major speciality chemical
player in China, one of the world's fastest growing markets.
</P>
<P>
He said the second phase of the park, targeted for completion
in 2000, will include space for companies in such fields as food
ingredients, fine-chemical production, packaging, and training and
development.
</P>
<P>
As the world's seventh largest producer of chemicals and
pharmaceuticals, Rhone-Poulenc has established 17 joint ventures
and one wholly owned subsidiary in China, involving an investment
of 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the company's sales in China topped 200 million
U.S. dollars with a goal of 1 billion dollars by 2005.  
</P>
</TEXT>
