<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Clarifies Reports on State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The reported number of
state-owned enterprises that are in debt has been exaggerated,
Chinese Premier Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Salama Ahmed Salama, acting
editor-in-chief and first editor of the Egyptian newspaper
"Al-Ahram" on Oct. 17, Li said that the figure is less than the
reported estimates of 70,000 and higher.
</P>
<P>
Li said that many state-owned enterprises in China are
well-run, especially those in the country's key industries.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises suffering losses are mainly in traditional and
special industries, he said, such as machinery, textiles,
nonferrous metallurgy, chemicals and defense.
</P>
<P>
The losses are inevitable in the process of restructuring the
economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 80,000 state-owned enterprises. More than
80 percent of those are small, he said, and only one-third are
losing money. More than 80 percent of those losing money are small
enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said, in terms of the total, the ratio of state-owned
enterprises losing money is very high. However, since small
enterprises account for a small proportion of the total asset
value, sales revenues and profits, he said, the total loss is
relatively insignificant. He stressed that most large state-owned
enterprises are making money.
</P>
<P>
For example, the 512 key state-owned enterprises receiving top
priority from the central government account for less than one
percent of state-owned enterprises. However, they account for 55
percent of total assets, more than 60 percent of sales revenues
and 85 percent of profits and taxes paid to the government.
</P>
<P>
In the process of shifting to a market economy, he said, a
considerable number of state-owned enterprises encountered some
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
Li said reforming state-owned enterprises is the key point of
China's economic restructuring. "We will focus on invigorating the
state sector of the economy as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that, to attain this goal, a modern enterprise system
must be introduced and state enterprises must be strategically
reorganized.
</P>
<P>
The major ways to do this, he said, are properly managing
large enterprises while relaxing control over small ones, enabling
efficient enterprises to prosper while eliminating the inefficient
ones, and increasing efficiency by downsizing staff.
</P>
<P>
The government will concentrate its resources on beefing up
major enterprises with established advantages, making small
enterprises prosperous by relaxing controls, and combining the
reform of state-owned enterprises with their reorganization,
upgrading and improved management, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government encourages superior enterprises to
take over inferior ones, and allows money-losing companies to go
bankrupt. Laid-off workers receive assistance in finding new jobs
and enterprises are relieved of excessive debt and unreasonable
burdens.
</P>
<P>
These measures already are bearing fruit, Li said. As a result,
more and more state-owned enterprises have changed the way they
operate and increased their competitiveness in the
marketplace. The general situation of state-owned enterprises is
improving, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China has
put forward a series of explicit measures to accelerate the reform
of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We have the confidence to get most of the state-owned
enterprises out of the doldrums through unremitting efforts," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Check Unemployment at Reasonable Level: Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China has an unemployment rate
of about three percent and the government is trying to retain it at
a "reasonable" level, Chinese Premier Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Salama Ahmed Salama, acting
editor-in-chief and first editor the Egyptian newspaper "Al-Ahram"
on Oct. 17, Li said that unemployment in urban areas is nearly six
million. He said that the actual unemployment rate in urban areas
is probably higher than the registered figure of three percent.
</P>
<P>
"China does have a problem of unemployment," he said.
</P>
<P>
China has a population of 1.2 billion, he said, and the
government is trying hard to keep the unemployment rate at a
"reasonable level" by training laid-off workers for re-employment
and by increasing production.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of China's population is in rural areas; 13
million babies are born every year. Surplus labor has been one
result of higher productivity in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
This is a problem for every developed country and this problem
still exists in all countries, Li said, especially developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese farmers have built large numbers of
township enterprises by themselves since the beginning of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
"This is a great creation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that these enterprises have not only invigorated the
rural economy and increased farmers' income, but have also
provided job opportunities for many rural people. This will help
stem the flow of rural people into urban areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that, so far, township enterprises in the country have
taken in 120 million laborers. In addition, 60 million rural
people have gone from less developed areas to more developed
coastal areas for employment.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the coastal areas are in need of laborers for
economic development, while less developed areas have a surplus,
Li said there is a mutual need for a labor flow that benefits both
sides.
</P>
<P>
He said the duty of governments at all levels is to maintain an
orderly flow of labor, to protect laborers' legitimate rights and
interests and to safeguard social stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that some of rural laborers have learned production
skills and become the backbone of local enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Chinese government's policy on the growing
number of surplus laborers is to encourage the development of
township enterprises and service industries that are based on
local raw materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
