<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng Discusses Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The process of Hong Kong's
return to the motherland has strongly proved the feasibility of
China's "one country, two systems" policy, said Premier Li Peng in
an interview earlier this month with the Egyptian newspaper
"Al-Ahram".
</P>
<P>
Li said the successful return of Hong Kong has opened up
brought prospects for China's resumption of sovereignty over Macao
and resolution of the Taiwan issue in accordance with the policy of
"peaceful reunification and one country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has entered a new age in which Hong Kong people
administers its own affairs with a high degree of autonomy," Li
said.
</P>
<P>
Since its return to the motherland, Hong Kong, as an important
international financial and trade center, has played a great role
in advancing the nation's economy and promoting its ties with the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
China has in return given strong support for the sustained and
stable development of Hong Kong's economy and provided convenient
conditions for the region apart from being an extensive market to
it.
</P>
<P>
A large share of Hong Kong's entrepot trade volume results from
trade with the mainland, with the two parts forming a healthy
eocnomic tie based on mutual promotion and common progress.
</P>
<P>
Li said "one country, two systems" policy is an important part
of Deng Xiaoping's theories, which became the guiding maxims of
the Communist Party of China in its 15th Congress which convened
recently. The continued stability and development of Hong Kong
after the return reflects the sincere implementation of the "one
country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is an international metropolis, Li said, "and we
welcome countries and regions to conduct rightful economic and
cultural activities there so as to strengthen the links and
exchanges between Hong Kong and them as well as those between
China and the rest of the world. However, Li stressed, "we would
not allow any attempt to interfere in China's internal affairs by
taking advantage of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
