<HEADLINE> Laos Hands Over American Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Laos has handed over the remains
of a former American missing in action (MIA) Monday, according to
a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the handover ceremony for the remains of Lundy
Albro Lynn, Lao Deputy Foreign Minister Soubanh Srithirath said
that the Lao government had stuck to its humanitarian policy and
worked with the U.S. government over the last decade to
investigate MIA cases which dated back to the war in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that at least 66 of the 550 MIA cases, which were put
forward by the U.S. side, had been settled.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Wendy Chamberlin, U.S. Ambassador to Laos,
also expressed the appreciation of the United States and American
people.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the president of the United States and the
American people, I wish to express my deepest gratitude to the Lao
government and to the Lao people for your humanitarian cooperation
in our joint efforts to achieve a full accounting for Americans
missing in Laos," she said.
</P>
<P>
She also added that the U.S. government would continue to
pursue every opportunity to provide assistance in addressing Lao
humanitarian concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
