<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Destroy Last Batch of Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will destroy
its last batch of 1,000 stockpiled anti-personnel landmines
(APLs) this week, local daily, The Star, quoted military sources
as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
The detonation program, involving 260,000 landmines, began in
May and received worldwide publicity as a positive move towards
eliminating mines, which are estimated to cause 26,000 deaths or
injuries worldwide every year.
</P>
<P>
South Africa promised to destroy landmines early this year,
but it noted that a limited and verifiable quantity of APLs were
to be kept in storage "solely for training specific military
personnel in demining techniques and for research into the
demining process".
</P>
<P>
"All demining training and research will be carried out under
the strictest government supervision and control," South African
National Defense Department reiterated Monday.
</P>
<P>
The detonation is to take place Thursday at Alkantpan test
range, near Copperton in the Northern Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been making efforts to ban the production,
use and sale of landmines, and was one of more than 100 countries
and organizations which met in Oslo, Norway, recently to hammer
out a treaty banning APLs.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will be formally signed at an international
conference in Ottawa, Canada, in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Generators Added to Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Three more generating units
are expected to be added to the original two, which will begin
operation in 2003, as work on the Three Gorges Project has been
going faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Dafu, expert from the Yangtze River Water Conservation
Committee of the Ministry of Water Resources, said today that
increases would be required in static investment of 2.6 billion
yuan (about 300 million U.S. dollars) and in dynamic investment of
more than 5 billion yuan (600 million U.S. dollars) to carry out
the plan.
</P>
<P>
According to Yuan, the added generators will produce more than
26 billion kilowatts/hour of electricity, which means the Three
Gorges Project would make an additional 10 billion yuan (about 1.2
billion U.S. dollars) in output value.
</P>
<P>
Five turbo-generators are expected to be separately fixed in
2001, one year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
According to the original design, the first generator at the
left-bank water power station of the Three Gorges Project would be
put into operation in 2003, and the first one on the right bank
would begin producing electricity in the beginning of 2007. The
total of 26 generating units would be put into operation in 2009.
</P>
<P>
The water level at the temporary dams will be raised from 135
meters to 142-145 meters, which should improve the project's
capacity for regulating floods and improving navigation, Yuan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
