<HEADLINE> Abacha's Candidature of Presidency Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state general
Sani Abacha cannot contest any election because he is not a
registered member of any political parties in the country,
according to Information and Culture Minister Walter Ofonagoro.
</P>
<P>
"The mind of the head of state at the moment is not in the
presidency of the fourth republic," the minister said, adding
that "it is people who are trying to drag him in."
</P>
<P>
According to press reports today, the minister also advised
Nigerians to be more interested in the success of the transition
program and not who becomes the president.
</P>
<P>
At present, he stressed that they should be concerned about
electing credible people into the house of assembly on December 6
this year and in subsequent elections.
</P>
<P>
Ofonagoro, who is also the spokesman of the government,
reiterated the government decision that no officials are allowed
to participate in the election while still holding his or her
positions.
</P>
<P>
There was no chance for anybody in the present administration
to evolve into anything in the coming civilian government except
he or she resigns and contest elections at the ward level, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to the military government's three-year transition
program, presidential election will be held next year, with the
elected government taking power from the military on October 1
next year.
</P>
<P>
it has become a hot topic in Nigeria whether Abacha should
quit the military and participate in the election. Abacha himself
has said it was a matter that one should think about and it would
depend on the will of his continuity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
