<HEADLINE> India's Trade Deficit Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- India's trade deficit
increased to 2.50 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of the
current fiscal year (from April to September) as against 1.81
billion dollars in the corresponding period of fiscal 1996, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The higher trade deficit was on account of a 7.6 percent growth
in imports during the period which outpaced the export growth of
4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the data released by the Indian Commerce Ministry
here Monday, exports during April-September 1997 was 16.82
billion dollars compared with 16.14 billion in the same period of
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
This represents a growth of 4.2 percent, indicating that the
sustained slowdown in the country's export since 1996 has not been
overcome yet.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary estimates, imports during
April-September 1997 stood at 19.32 billion dollars compared with
17.95 billion in the same period of the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
