<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slumps to New Low Before Rebounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar plunged
to a four-year low today following dramatic falls on Wall Street
and in domestic shares, before bouncing back more than one U.S.
cent to close stronger on the day.
</P>
<P>
In a volatile session, the local currency reached a new low of
68.18 U.S. cents in morning trading, a level not seen since
December 1993, and a high of 69.75 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 69.25 U.S. cents, up from Monday's
close of 68.61 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Moore, St. George Bank foreign exchange trading manager,
said it had been a very volatile day for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Moore said the local unit came under pressure following the
fall on Wall Street overnight and the 10 percent decline today in
the Australian Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
But he said aggressive buying of the local currency by one
American institution in particular had pushed the Australian
dollar up through 69 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Traders also said there were unconfirmed rumors in the
financial markets that the Reserve Bank of Australia had been
buying up the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"People are sitting back and trying to keep their noses clean
at the moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All eyes will be on Wall Street. There is plenty of
nervousness and plenty of uncertainty," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the close the Australian dollar was at 88.58 Japanese yen
from 83.69, and against the Deutsche mark it was at 1.1959 from
1.2140. 
</P>
</TEXT>
