<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese PLA Leader Meets Singapore's Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Fu Quanyou, chief of the
General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), said
he hoped to increase the friendship and cooperation at various
levels and in different fields between China and Singapore and
their respective armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu said China values very much the bilateral relations and the
relations between the two armed forces, which not only is in the
fundamental interests of the two peoples, but is also conducive to
their economic development and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Fu, who is also a member of China's Central Military
Commission, made his remarks here today in a meeting with Tan Keng
Yam, visiting Singapore deputy prime minister and defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Fu said this visit is an important one which will promote mutual
understanding, friendship and cooperation and turn a new page for
exchanges between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu told Tan that Chinese side places importance to this visit,
believing that it will promote development of relations between
the two countries and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu went on to say that China and Singapore are two friendly
neighbors, a traditional friendship that dates to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
After the two countries set up diplomatic ties, bilateral
friendship and cooperation have rapidly developed through joint
efforts, Fu said, and bilateral economic and trade cooperation
have been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Fu also briefed the visitors on China's domestic situation and
defense policy.
</P>
<P>
Tan said that Singapore and China have enjoyed very good
relations, and they have been cooperative in political, economic,
social and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Tan said he has visited China several times, but that this is
his first visit to China in his official capacity.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the development of relations between the
two countries and their armed forces is conducive to not only the
two countries themselves, but also to the peace and development of
the region. Tan said he hoped for further bilateral exchanges and
cooperation in politics, economy and defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
