<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 to Adopt Guidelines for Project Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The group of 15 developing
countries (G-15) will adopt a set of guidelines for implementing
projects to ensure they are streamlined and concentrated in
priority areas, G-15 Economic Affairs Officer Lim Aik Hoe said
today.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will be applicable immediately and cover mostly
technical aspects apart from providing more cohesiveness in the
way member countries undertake projects, Lim said while briefing
reporters after the fourth meeting of the Governing Council of the
Committee on Investment, Trade and Technology (CITT), here ahead
of the inaugural meeting of G-15 economic ministers on October 31.
</P>
<P>
"The projects should be feasible and beneficial to member
nations. They should deal with an area that is not already
covered... It is important that the projects should add value and
bring something new or required by member countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said member nations would not be bound to the
guidelines for approval of their projects but it would help them
in obtaining support from other member countries in the
implementation.
</P>
<P>
He said the G-15 economic officials at their meeting today
asked the private sectors in member nations to give greater
commitment in the grouping's business and investment programs.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that greater business involvement is required to
energize the work of the Business and Investment Forum (BIF), a
G-15 project, Lim said, adding member countries felt that much
more could be done to bring in the private sector into the
mainstream of the BIF.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the G-15 members will convene a seminar in New
Delhi, India, in January next year to share their experience and
look for ways to facilitate trade among member countries, Lim
said.
</P>
<P>
Intra-trade among G-15 countries totaled 72 billion U.S.
dollars last year against the 64 billion dollars in 1995. And the
grouping's total trade in 1996 rose 8.8 percent to 796 billion
dollars, accounting for 7 percent of global trade.
</P>
<P>
G-15 now comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt,
India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru,
Senegal, Venezuela and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Kenya will be admitted as the 16th member at the G-15 summit
here from November 3 to 5 which will discuss measures to be taken
for a more positive and constructive dialogue with developed
nations, according to a statement by the Malaysian Foreign
Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second time for Malaysia to host the G-15
summit. The inaugural summit was held here in 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
