<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to Uganda Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital investment to
Uganda has declined from 157 million U.S. dollars in May-June to
38.5 million U.S. in July-August, The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
The slow-down of the investment inflow was caused by the
budget speech read by the finance minister on June 12 this year,
Uganda Investment Authority (UIA) said in its July-August 1997
operating summary report.
</P>
<P>
The budget speech announced to abolish tax holidays as an
incentive to investors.
</P>
<P>
"Most potential investors were taking cautious steps seeking
for clarification on the new measures and revaluating their
investment dicision," the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, there were 40 planned projects expected to create
1,853 jobs in July-August, camparing 76 projects to create 4225
jobs in May-June, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The total approved projects since July 1991 were 2,275 at the
end of August 1997, with a planned investment of 3,799 million
U.S. dollars to create 157,738 jobs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
UIA is to create a national technology information unit and to
sponsor a survey of available technology in use, the operating
report said.
</P>
<P>
A private firm has been contracted to handle the work, the
paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
