<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denounces Zambian Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior South African
official today denounced a Zambian coup which happened early in
the morning, saying it was a bad news for African renaissance.
</P>
<P>
"The whole world will condemn what is happening in Zambia
today," Gauteng Premier Tokyo Sexwale told reporters soon after
he was informed of the Zambian coup.
</P>
<P>
Describing the coup as "bad news for this continent", Sexwale
said "the era of guns and tanks rolling out of the camps against
civilians has got to come to an end in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Soldier must remain in the barracks and only go out to defend
sovereignty and the borders, and to assist in emergencies,"
Sexwale said.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers led by Captain Solo (only name) announced the coup at
seven o'clock local time through Zambia News Broadcasting
Corporation. The anti-government soldiers surrounded the State
House, where President Federick Chiluba lives, and the buildings
of Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The coup leader threatened that Chiluba must surrender and
leave the State House, or they would take the State House by
force.
</P>
<P>
However, by 09:50 local time, Chiluba declared in Lusaka that
the coup had been aborted and the situation in the capital was
"firmly under control".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
