<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia's share market
suffered one of its biggest plunges today, losing 27 billion
Australian dollars (18.69 billion U.S. dollars) in value following
similar carnage on Wall Street and Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The 7.18 percent dive brought to 41 billion Australian dollars
(28.39 billion US dollars) the amount wiped off the market's value
in the past three trading days, and was the fourth largest fall in
percentage terms for the all ordinaries index.
</P>
<P>
Share prices plummeted across the board from the opening after
New York's Dow Jones Industrial Average suffered its worst ever
one day points decline.
</P>
<P>
When Hong Kong opened, the all ordinaries hit a low of 2210, a
10.8 percent or 267 point decline, before clawing its way back to
close 177.8 points down at 2299.2.
</P>
<P>
From its all time high on September 25, the market has lost 21
percent, with today's close its lowest since October last year.
</P>
<P>
In a sell off not seen since the October 20, 1987 crash, the
all ordinaries dropped 9.2 percent within minutes of the opening,
outstripping Wall Street's percentage losses.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones' 554.26 point dive to 7161.15, which surpassed
the 508 point crash of Black Monday, 1987, automatically shut
trading on the U.S. stock market for the first time since such
rules were adopted in the aftermath of 1987.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Don Hamson, Westpac Investment Management investment
director, said the market had redeemed itself in late trading as
investors took note of share values.
</P>
<P>
"It redeemed itself in the afternoon as people stopped
panicking and started looking at the value of stocks," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Fortune favors the brave... The whole market's been sold off
across the board and the bargain hunters are looking," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bellwether BHP staged an admirable recovery after plunging as
much as 1.59 Australian dollars to a low of 12.30 Australian
dollars to close just nine cents down at 13.80 Australian dollars,
which traders attributed to bargain buying in late trade.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto dropped a massive 2.047 Australian
dollars to 16.053 Australian dollars, reaching a low of 15.20
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mining company WMC fell as low as 4.15 Australian dollars
before closing 25 cents down at 4.90 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index shed 7.29 percent or 85.2 points to
1084.0 and the all industrials index lost 295 points or 7.14
percent to 3835.8.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 530.76 million shares worth 1.14 billion
U.S. dollars, with rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 516
to 139.
</P>
<P>
The banking index closed down 271.3 points or 5.45 percent at
4703.1 off a low of 4531.5 earlier in the day. National Australia
Bank lost 95 cents or 4.80 percent to 18.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank lost 66.5 cents or 6.82 percent to 9.085 Australian
dollars, Westpac sank 51.2 cents or 6.20 percent to 7.75
Australian dollars, off a low of 7.103 Australian dollars, and the
Commonwealth bank fell 55 cents to 14.90 Australian dollars after
earlier touching 13.70 Australian dollars. Macquarie Bank dropped
1.945 Australian dollars to 9.045 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 10.73 percent or 118.9 points down at
989.4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Stock Market Tumbles Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's stock
market was not spared in the whirlwind that hit global markets
Monday, with the Johannesburg Stock Exchange registering its
biggest one-day loss in eight years.
</P>
<P>
The all-share index closed at 6,763.2 points, down 405.6
points, or 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the index lost 326 points or 4.4 percent to
7,094.2 points in the wake of a 10-percent crash in Hong Kong's
stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's loss was a six-year high, only four point short of
the 330-point fall after the "Black Monday" crash on Wall Street
in October, 1987.
</P>
<P>
The all gold index closed at 894.9, down 62.1 points, or 6.49
percent Monday, while the industrial index closed at 8,360.0
points, down 423.0 points, or 4.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Rand also lost ground, shedding four cents to a two-month
low of 4.690 against the U.S. dollar, despite the intervention
from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's stock exchange, whose Thursday crash sparked a
worldwide slide, again led the way Monday with a 5.8 percent fall
in the Hang Seng index to 10,498.20 points.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, the Dow Jones industrial average index
suffered its biggest point drop in history on Monday, falling
554.26 points, or 7.1 percent, to 7,161.15 points.
</P>
<P>
Trading had to be halted for 30 minutes in the afternoon when
Dow slid 350 points, but the index kept falling after the
interval.
</P>
<P>
Other major world markets also suffered remarkable losses.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, Frankfurt's DAX index dropped 4.2 percent and in
London, the FT-SE 100 fell 2.6 percent, while Paris's CAC-400
plunged 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues ended
at 16,417.18 points early Tuesday morning, falling below the
16,500 line for the first time since August 1995. The Nikkei lost
3.65 percent, or 621.18 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
