<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plummeted on the
Singapore market today as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost 122.87 points to close at 1,497.03, hitting the
lowest level in five years.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the overnight sharp fall on the Wall Street and the
plunge in the Hong Kong market, the STII nose-dived immediately
after trading opened. It once reached 1,486.74 point at 3:45 p.m.,
down 133.16 points from the opening of 1,619.9.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume increased to 304.65 million units, valued
at 583.84 million Singapore dollars (about 369.52 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances 411 to 7, while 190 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Land was the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 30.79 million units. It was followed by
local computer maker IPC Corporation which had 12.24 million
shares traded. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land was next
with 9.59 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Faber 200 led the gainers of the day as it rose 5 cents to
finish at 0.575 Singapore dollars. Sincere Watch gained three
cents to end at 0.29 Singapore dollars, while electronics firm
Thakral was up one cent to close at 0.54 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, local computer sound card maker Creative 50
was the biggest loser as it declined 5.1 dollars to end at 35.7
Singapore dollars. Bukit Sembawang and DBS Foreign lost two
dollars each to close at 11.2 and 11.1 Singapore dollars
respectively. NBT fell 1.7 dollars to finish at 12.7 Singapore
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
