<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-Off Workers in China Get Preferential Terms for Reemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration for
Industry and Commerce (SAIC) has worked out a series of measures
to help find jobs for workers laid off from state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In a recent document, the SAIC urged all its subsidiaries to
expedite the registration of applicants for individually owned or
private businesses filed by laid-off workers. Fees are reduced or
exempted for these applications.
</P>
<P>
The documents needed for the application include a lay-off
certificate issued by relevant labor departments and an
identification card.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Statistics Bureau, jobless people in
China now number about 8 million, or 4 percent of its labor
force. Six million of those have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
More than 4 million laid-off workers have been re-employed.
</P>
<P>
In China, industrial and commercial offices are responsible for
handling the registration of enterprises as well as the management
of private firms. These offices can arrange temporary business
licenses for the laid-off workers who have special financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The SAIC has also called for preferential terms in bank credit,
business sites, and facilities needed by professionals and
technicians laid off by state enterprises to help them open
scientific, production, and export-oriented private businesses.
</P>
<P>
The SAIC also is encouraging laid-off workers to open businesses
and set up stalls in marketplaces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
