<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel: None Responsible for Failed Action in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 28 (Xinhua) -- An inquiry committee of the
Israeli army has ruled that the abortive naval commando raid into
Lebanon last month, in which 12 Israeli soliders were killed, was
only a case of bad luck with no one to blame.
</P>
<P>
Gabi Ofir, head of the committee was quoted in Israel Radio as
saying today that the failed action, that has caused a new
campaign in Israel calling for withdrawal of Israeli troops from
South Lebanon, was due to a random ambush but not an intelligence
leak.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this was an incidental ambush which was set up
in the field by the terrorist groups out of fear of an Israeli
army action and not on the basis of concrete information," Ofir
said.
</P>
<P>
Both Hezbollah and Amal guerrilla forces have claimed
responsibility for the attack on the Israeli commando, that was on
a secret mission on a night of September 4 near the village of
Ansariya, north of Lebanese city Tyre.
</P>
<P>
Ofir indicated that military intelligence had apparently
mistakenly assessed that there was a low probability that
guerrillas would plant bombs so deep inside their territory.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed repeatedly that none of the deficiencies in
the actions, carried by intelligence officers and the commando
squad itself, had any direct bearing on the failure.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel set up a 15-kilometer-wide buffer zone in South
Lebanon to stop cross-border attacks in 1985, Muslim guerrillas have
attacked its troops frequently and caused many casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
