<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion Hits Lebanon's University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A bomb exploded late last night
on the campus of American University (AUB) in Beirut, shattering
the windows of two faculty buildings and destroying a professor's
car. No casualty was caused.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese newspaper the Daily Star said that there is no
evidence yet on a possible linkage between the incident and the
current visit of John Waterbury, the first U.S. president of AUB
to come to Beirut in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Waterbury, appointed as the new AUB president in Lebanon in
July, is expected to take office early next year.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously there's link between the attack and Waterbury's
visit," the paper quoted a student of psychology as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They probably didn't want to hurt anyone but wanted to make a
statement," another student said.
</P>
<P>
Hours before the blast, Waterbury had praised the return of
stability to Lebanon in separate meetings with Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi and House speaker Nabih Berri.
</P>
<P>
No U.S. university president has served in AUB in Lebanon since
the 1984 assassination of President Malcolm Kerr. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
