<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coup in Zambia Aborted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba declared here today that a coup has been aborted and the
situation in the capital is "firmly under control".
</P>
<P>
In a short nationwide speech transmitted by Zambian
Broadcasting Corporation at 09:50 local time, Chiluba said "the
situation is firmly under control."
</P>
<P>
"The enemy is defeated. The victory is certain," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Zambians to go to work and not to be
"intimidated and frightened."
</P>
<P>
No shots can be heard in the capital at present.
</P>
<P>
A defense official told Xinhua on condition of anonymity that
the coup has been aborted and all the soldiers involved in the
coup have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
He described the coup as "a small problem" created by some
"drunken soldiers" from the army.
</P>
<P>
Some sporadic shots were heard in the capital after a coup
staged by a group calling itself the National Redemption Council.
</P>
<P>
All government offices and shops were closed earlier this
morning, and few cars were spotted except the armored vehicles
and military vehicles loaded with soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers led by Captain Solo (only name) who announced the
coup at seven o'clock local time through Zambia News Broadcasting
Corporation surrounded the State House, where President Frederick
Chiluba lives, and the buildings of Zambia News Agency have been
captured by anti-government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The statement made by the coup leader had demanded Chiluba to
surrender and leave the state house, or they would take the State
House by force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
