<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: 35 Weekly Labor Hours Won't Destabilize Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Labor Minister Tiziano
Treu said today that 35 labor hours in a week will not destabilize
the Italian government and the "negative predictions should be
avoided."
</P>
<P>
The government stability "would be safeguarded," said Treu,
counter-attacking the recent savaging by the Fiat Group of the
cabinet proposals to introduce a 35-hour working week.
</P>
<P>
Fiat senior officials had said that the cut of labor hours
would weaken the competitiveness of the Italian industrial
products.
</P>
<P>
However, Treu said that it was "wrong to speak about the issue
as if everything had already been decided," since the government
wanted the law to be passed in January with the consensus of all
parties and it would take at least three years for it to become
effective.
</P>
<P>
The work-week cut emerged from a recent crisis-averting deal
with the government's left ally the Communist Refoundation.
</P>
<P>
Employers have slammed the deal while unions have also voiced
doubts about interfering with collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the employers' association Confindustria stressed
today that the cost to business of introducing a 35-hour week
would have to be taken into account in any contract renewals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
