<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Damming Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI (Yellow River), October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow
River was successfully blocked at 10:28 a.m. today on a section 40
km north of Luoyang, an ancient capital in Henan province.
</P>
<P>
The dam work, which began on Sunday at 4:15 p.m., went well
because the flow was only 190 cu.m. per second. Its completion
marks the beginning of the construction of the Xiaolangdi
Multi-Purpose Water Conservation Project.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng, who presided over the project's
opening ceremony three years ago, said today, "The damming of the
Yellow River at Xiaolangdi marks a joyful step forward in the
history of taming the river," after Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun
announced the success of the damming.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the river is the birthplace of the Chinese
civilization, but it is also a source of great sorrow for the
Chinese. "Controling Yellow River floods and developing
its water resources have remained a top priority of the Party
Central Committee and the State Council."
</P>
<P>
When completed, he added, the Xiaolangdi project will be able
to control catastrophic floods that occur once every 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide a foundation for flood control on the
lower reaches of the river, water-soil conservation on the Loess
Plateau, and economic development on the middle and lower reaches,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show the water flow of the Yellow River once
exeeded 30,000 cubic meters per second and the river had breached
its banks for more than 1,500 times in the past 2,500 years,
claiming the lives of numerous people and causing catastrophes to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
the Chinese government has made great efforts to bring the wild
river under control. Both Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping have given
important instructions on controling the river. And President
Jiang Zemin has visited the Xiaolangdi project site.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Water Conservation Project is the second largest
in China, after the Three Gorges Power Project on the Yangtze
River. When completed, the project will help stop the 10-cm annual
rise of the bed in the lower reaches of the Yellow River, by
controling 93 percent of its 649,000-sq-km drainage areas.
</P>
<P>
The dam has other functions as well: ice-run prevention, silt
reduction, irrigation, and water supply.
</P>
<P>
It is also the largest World Bank-financed project in China and
the project that employs the largest number of foreign technicians
and experts.
</P>
<P>
John Anderson, Head Consultant of the project, told Xinhua, "The
Xiaolangdi Project shows that China needs the world and the world
needs China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman: Premier Li Peng to Visit Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng will
pay an official goodwill visit to Japan from November 11 to 16 at
the invitation of the Japanese Government, Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
the Sino-Japanese relations, Tang noted, adding that Premier Li's
visit will help both sides to further increase mutual
understanding, expand common ground and promote a sound and steady
development of the good-neighborly and friendly relations and
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Premier Li Peng will meet Emperor of Japan
and hold talks with Prime Minister Hashimoto. He will also make
extensive contact with the Japanese people both within the
government and without, Tang disclosed.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Tokyo, Premier Li Peng will also visit Nagoya,
Osaka and Nara.  
</P>
</TEXT>
