<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are the major news
items in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
New Nigerian
</P>
<P>
-- The Commonwealth heads of government announced Monday in
Edinburgh, Scotland, that Nigeria would remain suspended from the
organization but no new sanctions would be taken against the
country at the moment.
</P>
<P>
-- Sierra Leone's ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah said
Monday that he would seek European Union assistance to rebuild
his country torn by internal conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian
</P>
<P>
-- The Nigerian head of state, General Sani Abacha, cannot
contest any election because he is not a registered party member,
Minister of Information and Culture Walter Ofonarogo said over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States has endorsed the new peace plan for
Sierra Leone between west African countries and the military
junta in that country over the resolution of the crisis triggered
off by the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
This Day
</P>
<P>
-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair has called on his fellow
heads of government of the Commonwealth to bring Nigeria back to
the fold of the 54-nation body "on the principles of good
governance and human rights".
</P>
<P>
-- The frosty relations between Nigeria and the United States
may soon improve as the state department holds a special
conference on the country today as part of a general policy
review on Africa.
</P>
<P>
Vanguard
</P>
<P>
-- Fiscal policies of the Nigerian government resulted in a 20
billion Naira (about 240 million U.S. Dollars) surplus in the
first eight months of this year following appreciable increases
recorded in oil and non-oil revenues during the same period.
</P>
