<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Plunge on Worst-ever Loss in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo plunged
this morning following the worst-ever point loss in Wall Street
overnight, with the key Nikkei index falling below the 16,500 line
for the first time since August 1995.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended the two-hour morning
session at 16,417.18 points, down 621.18 points, or 3.65 percent,
from Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues on the major
section, dropped 43.14 points, or 3.29 percent, to 1,269.31.
</P>
<P>
Traders rushed to sell issues across the board, renewing their
offering prices after the 30-share Dow Jones Industrial Average
fell 554.26 points, or 7.2 percent, to 7,161.15 on Monday, the
worst-ever point loss in Wall Street since the 1987 "Black Monday."
</P>
<P>
Voicing concern over impact of New York plunge on the Japanese
economy, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, government officials
and business leaders said today that they will closely watch
movements in Wall Street, and their possible impact on the
Japanese market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
