<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Polystyrene Joint Venture In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Shell recently signed an
agreement with the Jinling Petrochemical Corp. based in Nanjing,
the capital of east China's Jiangsu province, on the establishment
of a joint venture to produce polystyrene.
</P>
<P>
The venture, the "Jinling Shell Petrochemical Company", will be
owned by two subsidiary companies of Shell in China (60 percent) and
the Jinling Petrochemical Corporation.
</P>
<P>
It will be modernized with advanced technology and its capacity
increased to 28,000 tons annually by the year 2000, at a total
cost of 30 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The polystyrene will be used for insulation and protective
packaging. Shell is one of the major producers of this type of
polystyrene. The market in China is growing fast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Trades Become Popular Among Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The service trade, a
long-neglected sector in China, is now busily re-employing the
laid-off workers in Taiyuan, capital of north China's Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred jobless workers have been hired by individuals
or businesses to take care of a number of routine tasks, according
to an official source.
</P>
<P>
All the districts in Taiyuan have set up family service centers
to provide a wide variety of assistance to many urban families,
such as housecleaning, laundry and cooking, nursing the sick and
accompanying children to school.
</P>
<P>
Many of the laid-off workers have been employed by businesses
to clean windows and carpets in office buildings.
</P>
<P>
The city governments have offered some preferential policies
for the re-employment of jobless workers, including exemption from
industrial and commercial taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Trade With U.S.: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Zeng Peiyan, leader of the
Chinese Economic and Trade delegation, today expressed his
optimism about the future development of Sino-U.S. economic and
trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Zeng told a press conference that his is the sixth Chinese
Economic and Trade Delegation visiting the United States.
</P>
<P>
After an eight-day visit to Los Angeles, New York and
Washington D.C., the delegation, the largest of its kind, has
reached or concluded a series of contracts and agreements with its
U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The total contracted value has reached 4.26 billion U.S.
dollars, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
He noted this indicated the Chinese government is very active
in adopting positive steps to settle the existing problems in the
Sino-U.S. trade.
</P>
<P>
China plans to buy more Boeing airplanes, purchase 700,000 tons
of U.S. wheat despite China's good harvest this year and increase
its cooperation with the U.S. in oil exploration and manufacturing
of engines for light trucks, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the visiting delegation announced that the Chinese
government has approved AETNA, the third largest insurance company
for life and health in America, to operate insurance business in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
China's National Space Agency and the U.S. Trade Representative
Office also signed the "Agreement on Pricing Comparability Factors
for Commercial Launching Service of Low-Orbit Satellite."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sun Zhenyu, deputy leader of the delegation, who is
also deputy minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation,
told the press that the Chinese government has realized the
sensitivity of its trade deficit to the U.S. politics.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side would cooperate with the United States in its
bid to promote its exports to China, Sun stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
