<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artist Plays Flute with His Nose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The audience at a nightclub in
northeast China's Fuxin city burst into deafening applause when a
middle-aged flutist ended his performance by playing a tune on the
instrument with his nose.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lianzhu, 42-year-old manager of the club, started honing
his nose-playing skills three years ago. He stuffed one of his
nostrils with cotton and blew into the flute with the other.
</P>
<P>
After six months of practice, he could skillfully play many
songs with his nostril, to the delight of many an audience.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is an accomplished musician, with more than 30 years'
experience of playing the flute. He also sings and plays other
musical instruments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airport for Disaster-Combat Set up in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A new airport has been
established in northern China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region
to help local farmers deal with natural disasters such as drought
and insect infestations.
</P>
<P>
The airport, built by the Hadat Livestock Farm in Hulun Buir
Grassland with the permission of the Civil Aviation Administration
of China, is believed to be the first airport designed primarily
to cope with natural disasters in China, according to a local
official.
</P>
<P>
The airport, with an investment of more than one million yuan
(about 120,000 U.S. dollars), was designed for use by the
Chinese-made plane "Petrel-650C" which is used in cloud-seeding in
times of drought and to spray insecticides in cases of
infestation. Pilots and ground-crew members from ethnic groups in
Inner Mongolia are being trained to fly and service the planes.
</P>
<P>
The Hadat Pasture, home of the Sanhe breed, raises more than
10,000 head of cattle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
