<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Reach Agreement to Strengthen Space Launch Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China and the U.S. today
signed an agreement on Pricing Comparability Factors for
Commercial Launch Services to Low Earth Orbit (LEO).
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Liu Jiyuan,
president of the China National Space Agency, signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement constitutes an important document for the Chinese
and U.S. governments concerning pricing adjustment factors for
commercial LEO launches, which is an amendment to and improvement
of the Memorandum of Agreement between the two governments
regarding the International Trade in Commercial Space Launch
Services, signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States have come to the agreement
following more than two years of studies and investigation.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky noted that today's agreement clarifies conditions
included in the pricing of launch services in a manner that
provides more information and greater certainty to industries
interested participating in this market.
</P>
<P>
The two sides believe that the signing of the agreement will
further their cooperation in the space market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
