<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparatory Meetings for G-15 Summit Begin in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Preparatory meetings for
the Group of 15 developing countries (G-15) summit began here
today to give final touches to the summit scheduled for November
3-5.
</P>
<P>
The fourth meeting of the Governing Council of the Committee on
Investment, Trade and Technology opened today to discuss ways to
enhance intra-trade and development cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow, the 39th meeting of the Personal Representatives of
the heads of government will be held.
</P>
<P>
These meetings precede the inaugural meeting of G-15 economic
ministers on October 31 which will look into joint approaches in
dealing with multilateral trade issues for the World Trade
Organization (WTO) meeting in Geneva next May.
</P>
<P>
WTO Director General Renato Ruggiero and United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) Deputy Secretary
General Carlos Fortini will be here for a dialogue with the
economic ministers Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the grouping will also convene their
15th session Saturday which is expected to give added impetus to
the summit during which Kenya will be admitted as the 16th member.
</P>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur is the G-15 summit venue for the second time after
playing host for the inaugural summit in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, formed in 1989 as a consultative forum for countries
of the South to intensify cooperation and forge common stand on
mutual issues, comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile,
Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru,
Senegal, Venezuela and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Total trade of the G-15 members in 1996 rose 8.8 percent to 796
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for seven percent of global
trade, with intra-trade reaching 72 billion dollars last year, up
from the 64 billion dollars in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
