<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stocks Plunge Amid Global Jitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Share prices at the Philippine
Stock Exchange today continued the downturn amid global jitters
which caused the slide of a number of stock markets in Asia and
America.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine market's composite index, a basket of 30
companies, nose-dived 117.16 points, or nearly 7 percent, to the
four-year low of 1740.18 points. It has fallen more than 1,000
points since the beginning of the Southeast Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
About 1.377 billion shares were traded with a total value of
1.757 billion pesos (50 million U.S. dollars). Losers outpaced
gainers 118:6 and 27 kinds of shares remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Dealers and analysts said the local market has been influenced
by the overall situation of the global market in the past few
days. Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index crashed as much as 679.37 points
Monday and 1621.80 points to 8,876 at today's intra-day trading.
</P>
<P>
The currency crisis starting from Thailand in July has spread
to other parts of the world. Besides Southeast Asian nations,
shares in Japan, Australian, New Zealand and the United States
also fell sharply at today's trading session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
