<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Praises Yellow River Dam Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI (YELLOW RIVER), October 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
Premier Li Peng, speaking today at a ceremony to mark the
successful damming of the Yellow River at Xiaolangdi, called the
dam work a gratifying sign of progress made in taming the
river.
</P>
<P>
Li congratulated all the Chinese and foreigners involved in the
work, which started on Sunday and took more than 40 hours to
complete, on behalf of the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of China and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Li said that 1997 is an unusual year in the Chinese history and
that the country, which is still in the primary stage of
socialism, should take development of productive forces as its
major task.
</P>
<P>
Water conservation, which is part and parcel of the national
economy, is playing a bigger role in national economic growth and
maintaining social stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, China's second longest, is seen as the cradle
of the Chinese civilization, but it has also been the source of
many disasters. The CPC Central Committee and the State Council
have placed great importance on taming the river, and the
Xiaolangdi Dam is a major step taken by the Party and the
government in that direction, he said.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the project will be able to control
catastrophic floods that usually occur once every 1,000
years, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide opportunities for water and soil
conservation on the Loess Plateau and lay a solid foundation for
the economic development on the middle and lower reaches of the
Yellow River, Li added.
</P>
<P>
Today's ceremony was presided over by Niu Maosheng, minister of
water resources.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the ceremony were Jiang Chunyun, member of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and vice premier; Li
Changchun, member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee and secretary of the CPC Henan Provincial Committee; and
Ma Man Kei, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
