<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Anti-AIDS Cooperation Urged in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS epidemic which
threatens Asian economic development can be tamed through regional
cooperation and shared responsibilities, a senior official of the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) said today.
</P>
<P>
"The potentially grave consequences of a widespread AIDS
epidemic on economic development demand forward-looking,
anticipatory strategies to tackle the disease," ADB Vice President
Peter Sullivan said at the on-going 4th International Congress on
AIDS in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The five-day congress, which opened here Saturday, is designed
to explore ways to check the quick spread of HIV/AIDS in the
region. HIV is the human immuno-deficiency virus that causes AIDS
(acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
In his speech titled "HIV and Economic Development," Sullivan
warned that "the AIDS epidemic is the enemy of Asian promise."
</P>
<P>
"It threatens in a material way the progress that Asia has made
over the past several decades. It imposes huge economic costs on
societies, families and individuals, and endangers the economic
development of countries of Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"HIV/AIDS can be prevented, if not cured," he said, adding that
regional or multicountry approaches can be effective since there
are similarities in the nature of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
He said the public sector, non-government organizations, local
community organizations and the private sector "all have parts to
play" in fighting against the spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The private sector can play a major role by providing care
facilities, research and development initiatives and financial and
other types of contributions for HIV/AIDS activities, he
suggested.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has been promoting economic cooperation in the control
and prevention of HIV/AIDS in the Greater Mekong Subregion, which
is the hardest-hit area by HIV/AIDS in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
