<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Investigating Russian Access to Supercomputers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
investigating how Russia acquired U.S-made supercomputers that the
U.S. fears could be used to improve Moscow's nuclear warfare
capabilities, a State Department spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"There's no question that the Russians have those computers,"
spokesman James Rubin told reporters. "And we believe they are at
locations precisely where we did not want them to be."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. government learned last January that Russia
had acquired the computers and considered the matter so serious
that "it has been brought up at the highest levels."
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, U.S. companies sought Department of Commerce
licenses to export high-performance computers to ... weapons
labs in Russia. The application said the computers were in
ground water modeling and simulation," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"We did not approve these requests because of the risk of
diversion to nuclear weapons programs at these facilities," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States made clear that "Russian refusal to
cooperate in finding a mutual acceptable solution would
jeopardize joint U.S.-Russian cooperation and would result in
tightening of U.S. export controls vis-a-vis Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that Russia recently proposed moving the
computers from the weapons labs to other locations under an
agreement that would include U.S. monitoring.
</P>
<P>
"We view this idea with interest and hope the Russian
government makes a formal proposal that we can evaluate," Rubin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
