<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Take Up Encyclopaedia Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Asiatic Society of Bangladesh
(ASB) has taken up a massive project of compiling a ten-volume
encyclopaedia of Bangladesh, in both English and Bengali, sources
from the ASB said today.
</P>
<P>
Encyclopaedias in English are available in plenty, the sources
stated, adding that only one or two have been compiled in Bengali,
and their lives and usefulness were short-lived for one reason or
another.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, twelve selected scholars from
different disciplines have already written the outline of the
encyclopaedia and another 65 scholars have been selected to
scrutinise this draft.
</P>
<P>
The scholars have been divided into four panels and their task
will be to review the outline, and the outline will be finalised
after the panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
The outline has itself been divided into six subject-based
parts, covering the natural science, biological sciences, arts and
humanities, history and heritage, society and economy, and state
and governance, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
As each part will be looked after by a separate editorial
committee, there will be a central editorial board charged with
the overall responsibility of bringing out the whole.
</P>
<P>
The encyclopaedia is expected to contain a minimum of ten
thousand entries contributed by more than a thousand scholars from
both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
There is also a plan to preserve the encyclopaedia, when
completed, on a CD-Rom, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Thais Go Abroad This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The number of Thais traveling
overseas is expected to drop by 3.5 percent this year, compared
with double-digit growths during the past few years.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months this year, the number of Thais
making overseas trips totaled 1.1 million, down 1 percent from the
same period in 1996, and it is expected to be 1.78 million only by
the end of the year, down 3.5 percent from last year, according to
a report of Thai Farmers Research Center, available today.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, outbound travels by Thai people fell by 17.8
percent from the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the baht has made overseas trips 40 percent
dearer, while about 600,000 industrial workers have lost their
jobs so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Soaring consumer prices and tax increases have forced the
ordinary Thai people to cut back their spending on non-essential
items, including overseas tours.
</P>
<P>
Many Thais who had deposited money in the 58 finance companies
which had been suspended by the government for their huge debts,
are not able to get access to their money. The 58 finance firms
face either merger or closedown if they cannot raise enough money
to survive before a government-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
The government's belt-tightening policy encourages Thais to
spend their holidays in their home country.
</P>
<P>
The flagging economy has resulted in the closure of a number of
travel agents. Others are resorting to price-cutting just to
survive.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) hopes to
take advantage of the lower value of the baht to attract more
inbound tourists over the next two years. In December, the TAT
will launch the amazing Thailand campaign for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
