<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plummeted on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
(STII) nose-dived by 123.52 points to reach 1496.38 points at 11
a.m. hitting an all time low level in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Market watchers said that this is the first time since December
1992 that the market saw the STII fell below the psychological
support at 1500 points. They noted that the plunge came in the
wake of a sharp sell-off in regional stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets in Hong Kong, Malaysia, New Zealand, Australia,
Japan and South Korea were all down sharply in early trading. Hong
Kong shares fell by 849.14 points to 9649.06 points at the open.
</P>
<P>
In a chain reaction under the weight of Asia's financial
crisis, freefalls in New York and Europe fueled a new round of
losses as early trading began in Asia, market observers said.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrials Average Index lost
554.26 points, or 7.2 percent, and the New York Stock Exchange
halted trading for half an hour after the Dow fell by 350 points.
But the decline resumed once trading started again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
