<HEADLINE> Spain to Provide Soft Loans to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Spain has agreed to provide a
soft loan of 100 million US dollars to Indonesia, official sources
here said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding (MOU) signed here
Monday by Spanish Minister of Industry and Energy Josep Pique and
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, the loan will be used to
finance, among other things, feasibility studies on some
government-proposed projects in Indonesia, sources at the Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the feasibility studies, the loan will also be used
to finance several education and health projects, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
The MOU on financial cooperation was the realization of Spain's
pledge made during the sixth meeting of the Consultative Group on
Indonesia (CGI) in Tokyo in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Spain had also pledged financial aid to Indonesia
under the Intergovernmental Group on Indonesia's (IGGI's) scheme.
</P>
<P>
The IGGI is a grouping of donor countries and organizations to
Indonesia which preceded the CGI.
</P>
<P>
Spain's pledges to Indonesia since 1986 through the IGGI and
the CGI total 354.51 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
