<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Tries to Calm Investors After Stock Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government moved
quickly today to assure investors that market safeguards were
working effectively and the U.S. economy remained fundamentally
sound despite a sharp stock plunge.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to remember that the fundamentals of the
United States' economy are strong and have been for the past
several years, and the prospects for low inflation and low
unemployment are strong," U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
said in a brief statement.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the remarks after the Dow Jones industrial average
plunged by 554.26 points before automatic "circuit breakers"
halted trading before the normal market close.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the circuit breakers designed to stop
trading were used. The mechanism had been put in place as one of
the reforms following the stock crash of October 1987 when the Dow
fell by 508 points.
</P>
<P>
While today's sell-off was bigger in point terms, it was far
smaller in percentage terms because the Dow average is three times
the level of a decade ago. The 1987 crash represented a 22.6
percent loss in stock value compared with a 7.2 percent slide this
time.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the Working Group on Financial Markets -- the
interagency task force composed of officials at Treasury, the U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) and the Securities and Exchange Commission
-- had been convened for the first time and was closely keeping
tabs on market operations.
</P>
<P>
"Our consultations indicate that the payment and settlement
systems and other market mechanisms are working effectively," he
said.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry also told reporters
today that President Clinton was being kept informed of
developments in the Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
"The president is confident the fundamentals of the American
economy are strong," McCurry said. "We want everyone to just take
a deep breath and think about where we are.... Let's be calm and
reasonable."
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the market correction would likely keep the
U.S. Fed from raising interest rates for the rest of the year for
fear of being blamed for more instability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
