<HEADLINE> Thai Textile Sector to Benefit from Japanese Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan will provide Thailand
with equipment for textile product quality inspection, which will
help increase the sector's exports, according to a senior Thai
official.
</P>
<P>
The move will help upgrade Thailand's textile exports to reach
the standards required by international markets such as Europe and
Japan, the Bangkok Post today quotes Manu Leopairote, director
general of the Industrial Promotion Department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with the Japan International Cooperation
Agency (JICA), the Japanese government will also fund personnel
training to upgrade textile officials' expertise in textile
product development.
</P>
<P>
Thailand needs to move quickly towards producing high-end
products because it is losing competitive edge from its low-wage
neighbors, Manu said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's textile industry will also benefit from a
US plan to lift quota restrictions on 20 categories of textiles
and garments as of January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
Items under the US quota lift include child garments,
handkerchiefs, stockings, brassieres, cloaks, mixed silk and
fiber-made apparel, silk clothing, and carpets.
</P>
<P>
The US plan is in conformity with international agreements on
textiles and clothing. Under the World Trade Organization's
agreement, the garment trade will have to be liberalized in three
phases by the year 2004.  
</P>
</TEXT>
