<HEADLINE> China Develops Environmental Law Framework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- China has passed a set of
environmental protection laws, marking the country's environmental
law framework has taken shape under the fledgling market economy.
</P>
<P>
There are six environmental laws and nine natural resource
laws, according to Wang Yuqing, vice-director of the State
Environmental Protection Bureau, at a national meeting on
environmental laws and regulations, which was recently held in
Dalian, a coastal city in northwest China's Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
A number of administrative regulations have also been passed by
central and local governments, and China has signed a dozen
international environment agreements.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, China's highest legislative body, passed or
revised laws on the prevention of air and water, solid waste, and
noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
China has also begun drawing up laws on controlling pollution
from chemicals and radioactive materials, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
