<HEADLINE> Guangdong Sets Unified Bottom Line for Aid to Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 28 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has standardized its bottom-line living guarantee for
urban and rural people, leading all Chinese provinces in the
effort.
</P>
<P>
All its 142 cities, prefectures and counties set up a unified
minimum living standards for the poor, said Xu Daosheng, director
of the Provincial Department of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will offer financial aid to all the
poor in cities and rural areas -- the first move of the kind made
by a provincial authority in China.
</P>
<P>
"From now on, any Guangdong resident who lives in poverty can
receive financial support from local civil affairs departments,"
Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, an economic powerhouse in China, has aided 240,000
needy people, with 150 to 250 yuan given to urban residents, 100
yuan for small town residents and 80 yuan for villagers a month.
</P>
<P>
It has already given 84.7 million yuan (about 10.2 million US
dollars) to poor families as part of the standardization program.
</P>
</TEXT>
