<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Bulgarian Professional Soldiers Start Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-nine of the 120 announced
vacancies in the Bulgarian army have been filled by professional
soldiers, the army said.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Georgi Ananiev said the campaign for
recruiting professional soldiers ended on October 22 and it had
been partly successful.
</P>
<P>
What was important was that a start had begun in the gradual
professionalization of the army, he said.
</P>
<P>
The process had three envisaged stages -- going from an
experimental start to a mixed, professional-conscript principle of
army building. The formation of entire units of professional
soldiers was expected by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
By law, professional soldiers should not be paid less than
average wage. The first group of professional soldiers will start
with a monthly pay equivalent of 89 to 120 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The minimum wage in Bulgaria is something worth 25 dollars and
the unemployment rate has reached 13.63 percent, and even higher
among young people.
</P>
<P>
Professional soldiers will also enjoy some privileges, such as
free life insurance and medical care.
</P>
<P>
Professional military service attracted not only unemployed
youths but university graduates. There were also cases of reserve
officers and sergeants wishing to give up their ranks to become
professional soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Experts reported weaknesses in publicity of the campaign,
especially in the provinces. Fund shortages were a main obstacle.
</P>
</TEXT>
