<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Police on High Alert in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Following intelligence reports
of possible rebel bomb attack in the downtown area of Colombo, the
Sri Lankan police further tightened up their security which has
been high already, well-informed sources said today.
</P>
<P>
There were claims in certain security circles that the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) was on the verge of
launching another major bombing campaign in the heart of the Sri
Lankan capital, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The warning came two weeks after a truck-bomb exploded in the
city center which resulted in heavy casualties and multi-million
U.S. dollar losses.
</P>
<P>
Though key security establishments in the city have been put on
alert, the authorities were unable to identify the facilities
being targeted by the LTTE, the sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The government on Monday requested foreign diplomats to avoid
being in this potentially dangerous area and cautioned hotels and
government institutions to be wary of fresh bombing attack,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The authorities placed new restrictions on traffic in the city,
under which unattended vehicles could be towed away by police.
</P>
<P>
The security forces sealed off Colombo on Saturday and
conducted a massive crack-down operation in which around 1,000
people were detained.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the security forces were doing their utmost to
hound out the rebels hiding in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
