<HEADLINE> Peruvians to Continue Talks With Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori said today his government will continue to pursue
dialogue with Ecuador in line with a border treaty signed in 1942
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori made the remark at a meeting with top military
officials. He stressed that talks with Ecuador must rely on the
Rio de Janeiro Protocol signed in 1942, which established the
definitive limits of the Peru-Ecuador border.
</P>
<P>
A government release said Fujimori instructed the armed forces
to take preventive actions in order to avert possible clashes
between troops of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Peruvian Foreign Minister Ferrero Costa
refused to grant Ecuador a free and sovereign pathway to the
Amazonas River. Ecuador's territorial demand led to demonstrations
in Lima and other Peruvian cities.
</P>
<P>
But Peruvian authorities say they are willing to attend the
second round of talks with Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador and Peru had been embroiled in border disputes since
their independence in the early 19th century, culminating in a
large-scale conflict in January 1995. A cease-fire was achieved
following mediation by the Rio De Protocol Countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
