<HEADLINE> Thailand to Lure Unemployed Back to Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Ministry of
Agriculture and Cooperatives will seek funds for a program to
attract unemployed industrial workers back to farms.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, which will need government budgetary
support, those who return to the countryside and work in the farm
sector will get loans from the funds at low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the year, about 600,000 industrial workers will
lose their jobs, according to a government report.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture ministry is devising incentives for the
laid-offs to go back to farming and related activities, according
to Pitipong Puengboon, deputy permanent secretary of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said tax on unutilized land should be raised to persuade
owners to lease their land to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Enforcement of land leases would also be relaxed under the
program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Current regulations set a minimum lease term of five years, but
many land-owners are reluctant to make such long-term commitments
in case land prices rise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
