<HEADLINE> Foreign Oil Companies Threaten to Leave Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Four foreign oil companies today
threatened to cancel their investments in Ecuador if the
Ecuadorian government refuses to abide by its debt duties, a
government source said.
</P>
<P>
The four companies, Argentina`s oil company YPF, the United
States` Western and Oryx, and French Elf, sent a communique to
President of Ecuador Fabian Alarcon last week. It said they may
have to stop their exploration and exploitation if they are
not paid what the government owes them.
</P>
<P>
In July, the companies requested the President to pay them 100
million dollars for their investments in accordance with contracts
signed with the state.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador produces 390,000 barrels of crude oil per day, 84
percent of which is extracted by Petroproduccion, a branch of the
state-owned Petroecuador. The rest comes from foreign oil
companies working in the country.
</P>
<P>
Oil exports amounted to 290,000 barrels a day and are the
backbone of Ecuador`s economy, making up 45 percent of the total
state budget. 
</P>
