<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peasant Woman's Cloth Tiger To Be Printed on Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 28 (Xinhua) -- A lovely cloth tiger will be
hunted by tens of millions of Chinese stamp-collectors next year.
</P>
<P>
The design of the tiger, created by Gao Qiuying, a 52-year-old
female farmer in north China's Shanxi Province, will be printed on
a set of stamps to be issued early next year, said a source from
the Chinese Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The ancient Chinese astrological chart is represented by 12
symbolic animals -- the rat, ox, tiger, hare, dragon, snake,
horse, sheep, monkey, cock, dog, and the pig -- with one animal
representing a year in a 12-year cycle. 1998 will be the year of
tiger.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, China has annually issued a set of stamps featuring
that year's symbolic animal. The stamps have become favorites of
Chinese stamp collectors.
</P>
<P>
Next year's tiger stamp will be the 19th set of the kind.
</P>
<P>
Gao's design was selected from several hundred entries
submitted by Chinese folk artists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
