<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facelift of Forbidden City Nears Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- The Forbidden City in central
Beijing, once the home of emperors but now one of the world's most
famous museums, is being refurbished to restore it to its original
look, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 old houses will be reconstructed to line the moat
where barracks used to be situated, said Li Deshan, an official
with the ancient architecture department of the Palace Museum, the
name now given to the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
Residential buildings currently occupying the site will have to
be torn down to make room for the planned construction. A
committee will be set up by the State Cultural Relics Bureau and
the Beijing municipal government to be responsible for the
relocation of residents, said Li.
</P>
<P>
In the Ming dynasty (1368-1644) the imperial city housed more
than 700 soldiers in rooms in surrounding walls on three sides of
the palace, the city gate on the south side being the exception.
</P>
<P>
Work will also be undertaken to dredge the moat and plug the
480 sewage outlets in the water, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
