<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK (Xinhua) -- Scientists at U.S. company Zerox's
research center in Palo Alto, California, announced Monday that
they developed a blue diode laser beam preluding a new generation
of high-speed laser printing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough occurred on October 14 when a team of Zerox
scientists demonstrated a gallium nitride-based blue diode laser
under pulsed current-injection conditions at room temperature, the
company said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Despite much work to do to reach the point of commercial
application, the new technology reassures Xerox' leading position
in the printing industry, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average joined the worldwide sliding and plunged 550 points to
7161.15 Monday, giving the worst single-day point drop in the
history of the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Trading had been halted for half an hour earlier in the
afternoon when the Dow was down 350 points. But it kept on falling
after that.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index also set a record.
It was down 115.66 points, its largest drop in history.
</P>
<P>
The markets around the world were triggered again by a 6
percent drop in Hong Kong's Hang Seng index Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo Monday, the Nikkei stock average fell 1.9 percent.
Frankfurt's DAX index dropped 4.2 percent, London's FT-SE 100 fell
2.6 percent, and Paris' CAC-400 dropped 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Leading stock markets in Europe all tumbled Monday
and ended sharply lower, depressed by more turmoil in Asian
markets, decline on Wall Street and UK's stance on European single
currency.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index in London fell by more than two percent or
129.50 points to end at 4,840.7, below the 4,900- point level as
Wall Street slipped further into the red and the British
Chancellor Gordon Brown ruled out early UK entry into European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended more than four percent lower,
hit by the continuing slump in share prices on Hong Kong's Hang
Seng index.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a prolonged financial crisis in Asia also unsettled
the Paris bourse, as much of corporate France is strategically
exposed to Asian markets. The CAC-40 index ended down 79.39 points
at 2,769.64.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Snowstorms in the Plains in the United States
during the weekend led to at least 10 deaths and left hundreds of
thousands of people without power in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
The first big snowstorm of the season dumped 22 inches of snow
on Denver, the city's worst for October, and record snowfalls were
registered in parts of Iowa and Nebraska. In the Colorado
foothills, snow piled up to 50 inches in Coal Creek Canyon, about
33 kilometers west of Denver.
</P>
<P>
The blizzard knocked out power to hundreds of thousands of
people from the Plains to the Great Lakes. As many as 230,000
homes and businesses were blacked out today in Michigan and more
than 70,000 were without power in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Federal Maritime Commission (FMC) Monday
approved a settlement with Japanese carriers ending a dispute that
had threatened to close American ports to Japanese cargo ships.
</P>
<P>
It was learned here that the settlement was reached after
Japanese shipping companies agreed to pay 1.5 million U.S. dollars
as a fine to settle their disputes with the FMC.
</P>
<P>
"While we continue to believe that the FMC's actions were
unfair, unwise and illegal, the carriers reluctantly agreed to
make this payment in the interests of removing any further threat
of sanctions and moving the reform process forward," an attorney
for the Japanese shipping lines said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The protracted disputes flared up earlier this month when the
FMC threatened to bar Japanese ships from the U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian state grain production totaled 84.7 million
tons, 16.3 million tons more than 1996, and the yield had risen
0.3 tons to 1.94 tons per hectare, the Interfax quoted Ministry of
Agriculture and Food's crop chief Ivan Gridasov as reporting
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, only 9 percent of the crop area,
600,000 hectares of grain, left to harvest as of October 25.
</P>
<P>
Gridasov said that 294,000 hectares of maize had been cleared,
44 percent of the crop area and 104,000 hectares more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Russia is expected to produce about 85 million tons of grain in
all this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The military government in Sierra Leone executed 10
people at the weekend by firing squad after they were alleged
found guilty of crimes ranging from murder to looting.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted a military official as
saying that the execution was to send a signal to the unruly
soldiers and to reassure the civilian population of their
allegiance to the peace accord signed last Thursday with west
African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
