<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Once Threatened Bird Species Thriving in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- After 17 years of efforts by
Chinese scientists, the crested ibis, an internationally protected
bird now only found in China, has increased to an estimated 100 in
number in Yangxian County, Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The rare bird used to live in the former Soviet Union, Korea
and Japan in the 1960s and 1970s, too. It has been threatened with
extinction because of low reproductive capacity and bad ecological
environment.
</P>
<P>
In China, the ibis had disappeared for 17 years before it was
refound in 1981, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
On May 23, 1981, Chinese scientists found seven crested ibises
in Yangxian, a mountain area far away from
industrial spots and large cities. And then a State level natural
protection zone for the bird was established in the county,
according to Zhong Gaoshi, director of the Shaanxi Protection
Association for Wild Animals.
</P>
<P>
In the past 17 years, Chinese scientists have made great
efforts in the protection and research of the bird. Artificial
propagation and incubation made the bird's numbers increase
rapidly, Zhong said.
</P>
<P>
Now an estimated 100 ibises have been living in the Yangxian
Natural Protection Zone.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the zone received 2.7 million Japanese yen
(22,310 US dollars) from the Japanese Bird Protection Union for
further protection research work on the bird.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Suffers From Fake Intellectual Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela loses more than 500
million dollars a year for the absence of a legal frame to curb
the traffic of intellectual counterfeit goods.
</P>
<P>
The National Council For Investment Promotion said protection
of intellectual property rights is an important matter in view of
trade between Venezuela and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The council's spokesman, Luis Soto, asserted the country should
foster the passing of a bill on the Intellectual Property Law
which was stalled in the Congress more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The bill should also be supported by a civil group against
violation on intellectual copyrights, he added.
</P>
<P>
The council reported that effective actions taken recently have
reduced sales of fake software in Venezuela, which percentage of
total software sales went down 68 percent in 1995 from 70
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Council registered an enhancement in the
application of the law in protecting intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, it said much remains to be done in Venezuela to
meet the standards required by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
