<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Islanders Benefit From Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 28 (Xinhua) -- Su Mingli, a Jing ethnic
minority farmer, has spent more than one million yuan to develop
tourism in his hometown of Wanwei Island, Dongxing City, Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China.
</P>
<P>
His restaurants and shops on the island receive more than 3,000
tourists every day. And more than 300 Jing islanders have
participated in the local government's effort to build up the
tourism market, pouring in a total investment of over 30 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Jing, one of China's smallest ethnic minority groups, has a
population of 20,000. They live in Dongxing's Wutou, Wanwei, and
Shanxin islands bordering Vietnam. In the past they made a living
from fishing, and were isolated from the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, they have prospered as a result of
border trade and deep-sea fishing. Wutou Island's more than 1,300
Jing families registered more than 6,000 yuan in per-capita net
income last year, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over 300 overseas firms have joined in the
development, with 125 million yuan in investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
