<HEADLINE> Goodwill Games to Be Held Outside U.S. and Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The 2002 Goodwill Games would
be held in the Far East or Oceania instead of the United States
and Russia, organizers said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the final site will be expected in
February.
</P>
<P>
The previous four Goodwill Games, launched by media magnate Ted
Turner to help smooth the strained U.S.-Soviet sporting relations
due to Cold War, alternated between sites in Russia and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The last Games, plagued by organizational problems, were held
in St Petersburg, Russia. And the 1998 Games will be in New York.
</P>
<P>
The Goodwill Games have redefined their "cause" and are now
dedicated to benefitting children. The Games' official charities
are the Boys and Girls Clubs of America and UNICEF
International.
</P>
<P>
Next summer's Games will attact 1,300 athletes from more than
60 countries competing in 15 sports. The 15-day competition has
total prize money of five million U.S. dollar and will be
broadcast to 150 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
