<HEADLINE> Chilean Players Threaten to Go back on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Chilean soccer players
threatened to go back on strike on Monday as the leader of their
union accused some clubs of breaching the agreement which ended
the first strike last month.
</P>
<P>
Union leader Carlos Ramos said that a new strike would be
proposed at a meeting on Wednesday if the clubs didn't respect the
agreements and solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said some clubs had fined or sacked players for taking
part in September's two-week strike, which had been aimed to
protest at "dismal working conditions".
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Arica club announced they were sacking their
entire professional squad for their participation in the strike
and planned to field a youth team for the rest of the
competition. 
</P>
