<HEADLINE> HK's National Games Champion Cyclist Rewarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Wong Kam Po, who won Hong
Kong's only gold medal at the recent Eighth National Games in
Shanghai, received a sum of 300,000 HK dollars (39,700 U.S.
dollars) as a cash incentive here today.
</P>
<P>
The prize money was given according to a National Games
Athletes Incentive Award scheme which was jointly presented prior
to the games by Hang Seng Bank and the Hong Kong Sports
Development Board (SDB).
</P>
<P>
Wong was named one of the games' Top Ten Athletes.
</P>
<P>
Wong's coach Shen Jinkang, a former head coach of China's
national cycling team, was presented here today by the bank with a
gold-plated souvenir plaque, for his contribution to the success
of the 24-year-old cyclist at the National Games.
</P>
<P>
John Hung, chairman of the SDB, promised at the rewarding
ceremony held at the Hang Seng Bank headquarters here today that
he would propose to the SDB authorities that Shen be given
"suitable financial support" in his future training.
</P>
<P>
A gold-plated souvenir plaque was also presented to young Hong
Kong table tennis player Wong Ching for her performance at the
National Games where she beat four-time Olympic champion Deng
Yaping. Wong was selected as one of the Best Potential Athletes
at the Shanghai games.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, now a special administrative region of China, sent a
168-strong delegation for its participation for the first time in
the National Games held in Shanghai earlier this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
