<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mark Rydell Attacks American "Blockbuster" Movies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 28 (Xinhua) -- American film director Mark
Rydell lashed out at the American "blockbuster" movies at the
ongoing Third Shanghai International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
Rydell, an international judge at this year's festival, was
asked by some journalists about whether those big movies are the
mainstream of American films. He flatly denounced the idea.
</P>
<P>
"No, it is a misunderstanding. It is a mistake for so many
movies to seek special effects," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some producers make lots of entertainment films to attract
teen-agers, but those films have no content, no art. Movies should
come back to the problems that human beings really need to solve,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Rydell was born in New York in 1934. He has directed many
award-winning movie scripts such as "On Golden Pond" and "The
River," and has received 28 Academy Award nominations.
</P>
<P>
This is Rydell's first visit to Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
