<HEADLINE> Jackson Leads Efforts to Restore Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Reverend Jesse Jackson
has brought thousands of supporters to California's Capitol in
Sacramento, seeking to restore affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
Jackson is targeting Proposition 209, approved by 54 percent of
state voters last November to abolish race- and gender-based
preferences in public hiring, contracting and education.
</P>
<P>
Now that the law has survived court challenges, Jackson says
it's time for President Bill Clinton to enforce federal civil
rights laws and overturn it.
</P>
<P>
Jackson suggested today that the federal government withhold
money for California programs if the state repudiates the vision
of Martin Luther King Jr. for an inclusive America, United Press
International reported.
</P>
<P>
On the other side of the Capitol, Proposition 209 supporters
invoked King as well in calling for a color-blind society --
without preferences.
</P>
<P>
Jackson's rally, involving about 10,000 people, was the latest
in a series against the initiative, beginning with a march across
the Golden Gate Bridge last summer. 
</P>
