<HEADLINE> Hussein: Jordan Continues Committed to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein said today
that his country continues committed to a just and comprehensive
peace in the Middle East despite various challenges.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark at a joint press conference here this
evening with visiting Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will continue to try to "help restore rights to the
Palestinian, Syrian and Lebanese people," the king said.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that he was disappointed with the current situation
between his country and Israel, which signed a peace agreement in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The third anniversary of the signing of the accord fell on
Sunday, but there were no celebrations planned for the historic
event.
</P>
<P>
The beginning of Jordan-Israel peace was "encouraging and full
of hopes, but the conditions had not remained the same all the
way," the king said, quoted by Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan-Israel peace treaty covers political, trade,
economic and other issues, but only one item, the full opening of
the border, has so far materialized.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries slumped after Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sent two secret agents to assassinate
a Hamas leader in Amman last month.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the only two Arab countries that conceived
peace with Israel. The other is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
