<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Sir Leon Brittan,
vice-president of the European Commission, the European Union
(EU)'s executive body, today flew to South Korea for high-level
meetings with its president Kim Young-Sam and his key ministers.
</P>
<P>
Top of Sir Leon's agenda will be trade liberalization talks,
including the signing of a bilateral agreement to open procurement
markets for telecoms equipment.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's National Assembly is currently considering a
far-reaching reform of the country's system of financial
supervision, the benefits of which Sir Leon is scheduled to
underline during the visit.
</P>
<P>
The EU believes that the potential reform will yield benefits
for South Korea in terms of greater financial stability and
stresses that this will be complemented by successful conclusion
of ongoing negotiations in the World Trade Organization on
financial services.
</P>
<P>
Brittan will also discuss the progress of the Korean Peninsula
Energy Development Organization, which is working to replace the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea's nuclear reactors with
safer, more proliferation-resistant models. 
