<HEADLINE> US, Japan Reach Agreement Over Shipping Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Maritime
Commission (FMC) today approved a settlement with Japanese
carriers ending a dispute that had threatened to close American
ports to Japanese cargo ships.
</P>
<P>
It was learned here that the settlement was reached after
Japanese shipping companies agreed to pay 1.5 million U.S. dollars
as a fine to settle their disputes with the FMC.
</P>
<P>
"While we continue to believe that the FMC's actions were
unfair, unwise and illegal, the carriers reluctantly agreed to
make this payment in the interests of removing any further threat
of sanctions and moving the reform process forward," an attorney
for the Japanese shipping lines said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The protracted disputes flared up earlier this month when the
FMC threatened to bar Japanese ships from the U.S. ports. Japan's
three major shipping companies had refused to pay 4 million
dollars in the FMC-imposed fines after the Japanese government
rejected the U.S. demand for reforming their port practices which
were alleged by the U.S. side as biased against foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Japanese negotiators reached agreement in
principle on most aspects of the dispute on October 17, but a gap
remained on whether the fines should be paid by the Japanese
shipping firms.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement requires final approval of the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the settlement
was consistent with the terms the administration had been seeking.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement would promote competition and increased
efficiency at Japanese ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
