<HEADLINE> Turkey Dissatisfied With German Stance Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said today that Germany should not take a negative
attitude toward Turkey's European Union (EU) membership bid.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Demirel said that German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl had assured Turkey that Bonn would help
pave the way for Ankara's EU membership issue, but their actions
"are now disturbing Turkey."
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel had reportedly told a EU
ministerial meeting in Luxembourg last weekend that Germany is
"sceptic" about the success of Turkey's EU bid.
</P>
<P>
Turkey can hardly be invited to talks on accession so long as
it fails to settle its conflict with the Kurds and improve its
human rights record, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has always been termed by Ankara as the biggest
obstacle for Turkey's success to be admitted into the European
body.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible for Germany not to know the value of
Turkey," Demirel said, "it is also against Bonn's own interests
to withdraw its support for Turkey."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president, however, expressed his belief that
Europe will be wise enough not to exclude Turkey from the EU
enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers gathered in Mondorf, a resort town in
Luxemburg, to discuss their strategy for talks with eastern and
southeastern European countries wishing to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU is scheduled to hold a summit meeting at the end of
this year to make decisions on the plan to start membership
talks with some prospective EU candidates.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been making efforts for full EU membership
but so far no positive results have been achieved due to its
differences with the EU, including the Kurds problem, the Cyprus
issue, human rights as well as its weak economy.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Deputy
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit visited some EU countries, such as
Germany, France and Sweden, to rally support for Turkey's EU
bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
