<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Iraq over Cutting Ties with U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Monday warned Iraq of serious consequences by suspending its
dealing with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. warning came after Iraq's parliament had earlier
recommended Iraq cut ties with U.N. special commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass destruction as a
gesture to counter a U.N. Security Council resolution threatening
more sanctions against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council last week approved a resolution
threatening to impose a travel ban on Iraqi officials alleged to
have hindered the inspectors from carrying out their work.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq decides to follow the assembly's advice, that would
have serious consequences," a White House spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman declined to comment on what the consequences
might be, only saying: "We have a wide range of options. I do not
want to go beyond that at this time."
</P>
<P>
He also said the U.N. weapons inspectors had not reported any
problems in their inspection and monitoring activities in the
last few days.
</P>
<P>
The White House spokesman called the Iraqi parliament's
recommendation "a crude attempt to intimidate the security
council", which he said would not be "successful."
</P>
<P>
"Iraq needs to understand clearly that it must cooperate with
UNSCOM's mission. UNSCOM must be given full and complete access
to the sites, documents and personnel that it seeks to fulfill
its mission," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
