<HEADLINE> At least 10 Reported Dead in Snowstorm in Plains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Snowstorms in the Plains in
the United States during the weekend led to at least 10 deaths and
left hundreds of thousands of people without power in the last two
days.
</P>
<P>
The first big snowstorm of the season dumped 22 inches of snow
on Denver, the city's worst for October, and record snowfalls were
registered in parts of Iowa and Nebraska. In the Colorado
foothills, snow piled up to 50 inches in Coal Creek Canyon, about
33 kilometers west of Denver.
</P>
<P>
The blizzard knocked out power to hundreds of thousands of
people from the Plains to the Great Lakes. As many as 230,000
homes and businesses were blacked out today in Michigan and more
than 70,000 were without power in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people had to seek shelters in airports, bus
terminals and along highways. As airlines sharply reduced flights
in the region, thousands of travelers were stranded at airports.
</P>
<P>
Schools in many communities were closed from eastern Colorado
into Iowa. Major highways had reopened today, but several roads
were still blocked by three-meter drifts in southeastern Colorado.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said that four people were found
dead in stranded cars, three of them from the cold and one from
carbon monoxide poisoning in east Colorado. An 11-year-old boy in
tiny Stratton, near the Kansas line, died after becoming lost in
the snow after sledding.
</P>
<P>
In Oklahoma, a 77-year-old woman who tried to walk from her
stranded car to her home was found dead in 18 inches of snow. Two
deaths were blamed on the storm in Nebraska, one in Illinois and
one in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
National Guardsmen had used helicopters, snowmobiles and
all-terrain vehicles to rescue stranded motorists or residents
from powerless homes.
</P>
<P>
Emergency shelters supplied warmth today for some of the
hundreds of thousands of people left without power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
