<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
all tumbled Monday and ended sharply lower, depressed by more
turmoil in Asian markets, decline on Wall Street and UK's stance
on European single currency.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index in London fell by more than two percent or
129.50 points to end at 4,840.7, below the 4,900- point level as
Wall Street slipped further into the red and the British
Chancellor Gordon Brown ruled out early UK entry into European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Brown ruled out entry during the life of this parliament but
said Britain must start to prepare for the future. His remarks put
downward pressure on the market which ended down for the fourth
session in a row and hit a two-month low.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended more than four percent lower,
hit by the continuing slump in share prices on Hong Kong's Hang
Seng index.
</P>
<P>
A poor performance on Wall Street on Friday and dollar weakness
also hurt market sentiment, leaving the DAX-30 index 171.75 points
lower at 3,879.12.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a prolonged financial crisis in Asia also unsettled
the Paris bourse, as much of corporate France is strategically
exposed to Asian markets. The CAC-40 index ended down 79.39 points
at 2,769.64.  
