<HEADLINE> Xerox Announces Breakthrough in Blue Laser Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at U.S. company
Zerox's research center in Palo Alto, California, announced today
that they developed a blue diode laser beam preluding a new
generation of high-speed laser printing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough occurred on October 14 when a team of Zerox
scientists demonstrated a gallium nitride-based blue diode laser
under pulsed current-injection conditions at room temperature, the
company said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Despite much work to do to reach the point of commercial
application, the new technology reassures Xerox' leading
position in the printing industry, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Supported by Pentagon's Defense Advanced Research Projects
Agency, the scientists are making efforts to create light-emitting
diodes and laser diodes that operate in the blue to green region
of the visible spectrum where the shorter wavelength of the beam
can result in a two-fold increase in printing resolution.
</P>
<P>
The spot diameter of a blue laser is half that of an infrared
laser, critical for color laser printing where accurate spot
placement and size control are necessary for higher quality work.
</P>
<P>
One way to create laser diodes is to lay down remarkable thin
layers of semiconducting materials.
</P>
<P>
Besides printing, the technology may be applicable to other
systems including high-capacity compact-discs.
</P>
<P>
Scientists also link blue laser's usage to military systems
including covert communications, biological warfare and missile
threat warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971028.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-27 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
