<HEADLINE> EU Official Urges Environmental Tax Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU) official
today urged the European Council to endorse environmental tax
reform which she believes has an important contribution to making
a cost-effective means of reaching environmental objectives.
</P>
<P>
EU Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard made the appeal at
a conference on environmental tax reform held today in Brussels,
saying that she "believes very much in the economic efficiency of
taxes creating incentives to change behavior."
</P>
<P>
She rejected the idea that all EU member states should go at
the speed of the slowest, saying that she is seeking to amend
Community legislation in the area of taxation in such a way as to
enable member states to press ahead while "taking care not to
fragment the single market."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner further underlined the need "to shift away
from taxes and charges on labor towards energy, natural resources,
waste and pollution."
</P>
<P>
She urged all the participants in the conference, from
industry, government, think-tanks or NGOs, to support the EU's
efforts to convince all the member states that environmental tax
reform is "valid, necessary, and can be put into practice
immediately by adoption of the proposal for an energy products
tax." 
</P>
