<HEADLINE> IFC to Finance Project to Alleviate Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 27 (Xinhua) -- In a move to create jobs for
thousands of Palestinians, the International Finance Corporation
(IFC) will help finance the first industrial estate catering to
small and medium industries in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
At completion, the project will employ up to 20,000
Palestinian workers in about 250 factories of various kinds,
according to a IFC news release sent to Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The IFC, the Palestinian Development and Investment Ltd and
the Board of the Palestine Industrial Estate Development and
Management Company (PIECO) signed the agreements on October 25.
</P>
<P>
A joint effort of the World Bank, the project will establish
PIECO, a private sector company which will build and operate the
Gaza Industrial Estate (GIE) at a cost of 39 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The GIE, to be located in the northeastern edge of the Gaza
Strip on a 48 hectares site leased from the Palestinian National
Authority, will include on-site infrastructure administration
offices and maintenance buildings, and 112 industrial plots.
</P>
<P>
"The project will help to alleviate the severe unemployment
that has been crippling the Palestinian economy," said Jannik
Lindbaek, the IFC executive vice-president, who is currently on
an visit to the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Because GIE is located within Gaza, its workers can have easy
access to their workplace; besides, GIE's location on the border
will facilitate greater integration of Gaza's economy with the
rest of the world, Lindbaek said.
</P>
<P>
Industries expected to locate at GIE include garment
manufacturing, plastics, food processing, other light
manufacturing, and information services.
</P>
<P>
IFC, the private sector arm of the World Bank Group, is the
world's largest multilateral source of equity and loan financing
for private sector projects in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The corporation has approved about 86.8 million dollars in
financing for seven projects costing about 165.3 million in the
West Bank and Gaza, with other investors contributing about 16.2
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
