<HEADLINE> Israel, Jordan to Cooperate in Red Sea Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Jordanian joint
committee on exploiting natural resources held a meeting today to
discuss further their cooperation between in the Red Sea area.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the meeting, Paez Tarona, chairman
of the committee from Jordan, said that the session was held on
the third anniversary of the signing of a peace agreement between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed peace with Israel in 1994, becoming the second
such country in the Arab world after Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Tarona noted that making peace with Israel was in accord with
the strategic goal of Jordan in the long run and would benefit the
future generations.
</P>
<P>
Tarona said that the meeting was going to focus on cooperation
between Jordan's Red Sea city of Akaba and its adjacent Israeli
city Eilat.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will explore ways to promote mutual trade
development in Eilat and Akaba, maintain the ecological
environment on the Red Sea coast, solve the problem of garbage
disposal and wipe out mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
Israel speeded up its economic cooperation with Jordan in an
attempt to remedy their strained ties in the wake of the bungled
Mossad attack on a Hamas leader in Amman last month.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to built a cross-border tourism
center in Eilat-Akaba area and jointly exploit water resources in
the Jordan Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
