<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: US Federal Deficit Lowest Since 1974 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal budget
deficit dropped to 22.6 billion U.S. dollars in fiscal 1997 ending
September 30, the lowest since 1974, U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced today.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the Democratic Leadership Council, President
Clinton said the federal deficit is down by 267 billion dollars
since he took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit in last fiscal year is the lowest
since 1974 when it was 6.1 billion dollars. The deficit is now
equal to 0.3 percent of America's gross domestic products (GDP),
also the lowest since 1970, the year after the U.S. government
recorded its last budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit hit a record high of 290.4 billion
dollars in 1992 and has been declining since that time, helped out
by an improving economy and the tax increases and spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
The White House and U.S. Congress reached a balanced-budget
agreement in August aiming at wiping out all the deficit by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government deficit is now lower than any other major
industrialized country and has declined to a point in relationship
to the overall economy that is viewed as insignificant by many
economists.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. government officials warned that tax cuts would likely
cause the deficit to increase next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
